<HEADLINE> China Generates 1,075 Billion KWHs of Electricity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- China generated 1,075 billion
kilowatt hours (kwhs) of electricity last year, a rise of 6.8
percent over 1995, according to a national power meeting that
opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Thermal power plants - coal and gas fired - produced 875.7
billion kwhs of electricity, up 8.5 percent over 1995 level, and
hydroelectric power stations produced 185 billion kwhs of
electricity, matching the previous year's level. Nuclear power
stations generated 14.3 billion kwhs of electricity.
</P>
<P>
Shi Dazhen, minister of China's Power Industry, said that last
year the tension between supply and demand in the country's power
industry eased up, coupled with a completion of pre-set goals for
power industrial production and capital construction, which has
effectively ensured a sustained, fast and healthy development of
the country's national economy.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the country finished the
construction of power stations with a combined generating capacity
of 12.8 million kilowatts in the past year. China also added 5,477
kilometers of power transmission lines in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Construction has started on the installation of two nuclear
power generating units for the second stage of China's
self-designed and built Qinshan Nuclear Power Station in east
China's Zhejiang Province, each with a generating capacity of
600,000 kw.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, 93.03 billion yuan (one U.S. dollar equals to
8.3 Chinese yuan) was spent on the construction of major power
projects in China, including 36.55 billion yuan of investment from
the state and 10.68 billion yuan from overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
The number of provinces and autonomous regions where
electricity is now available in every village reaches 12, said the
minister, adding that China will realize the goal of bringing
electricity within the reach of 95 percent of the country's rural
families and making electricity available in every county by the
year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
