<HEADLINE> Leaders of Cote d'Ivoire Meet Chinese FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABIDJAN, January 16 (Xinhua) -- President of Cote d'Ivoire
Henri Bedie held talks here today with visiting Chinese
Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen on bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
During the talks with Bedie at the airport, Qian spoke highly
of the friendly relations between China and Cote d'Ivoire, saying
that he expected the two countries to strengthen cooperation in
all fields.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the visit to China by Prime Minister Duncan
last July has enhanced the bilateral friendship and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Qian said China had opted for an African to run for UN general
secretary.
</P>
<P>
Qian also met Prime Minister Daniel Duncan and Foreign Minister
Amara Essy.
</P>
<P>
Essay said that his country has been pursuing the "One China"
policy and recognizes that Taiwan is an inseparable part of China.
</P>
<P>
He added that China, as a permanent member of the United
Nations, will play a greater role in international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Qian is making a stopover in Abidjan following his visit to Sao
Tome and Principe. He will proceed to Mauritania to continue his
five-nation tour of Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
