<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Hotel Profits Down in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The profit of Israeli hotels
dropped by 10 to 15 percent in 1996 compared to the previous year
due to "a combination of geopolitical factors.
</P>
<P>
Today's Jerusalem Post quoted Avi Rosental, director of the
Israeli Hotel Association, as saying that last year hotels showed
a 1.2-billion-US-dollar turnover, with 600 million dollars of
that coming from tourism.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, tourism from abroad witnessed a decrease of six
percent compared to 1995, with up to 20 percent fewer tourists
staying in Israel during the later part of the year.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed to the sharp increase in the number of
nights spent by Israelis in local hotels, which jumped by 12
percent in comparison with 1995.
</P>
<P>
"I think that this is a proof that Israeli hotels succeeded in
competing with all the vacation packages being offered in the area
because of our competitive price and our aggressive marketing, as
well as the fact that this winter, weather in Israel has been far
better than anywhere else in Europe," Rosental said.
</P>
<P>
Rosental noted that despite the slump last year, about 20,000
hotel rooms were either in the planning or building stage,
bringing the total up to about 50,000.
</P>
<P>
"Investors have to be optimistic and make long-term
forecasts, since it takes four or five years from the planning
stage to the opening of a hotel," he said.
</P>
<P>
The optimism, he said, was based on expectations for waves of
incoming tourists to mark Israel's 50th anniversary in 1998 and
the jubilee of Christianity in 2000 as a result of the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that even 50,000 rooms would not be enough if
millions come for the Christian event, but he added that there
were many examples around the world of hotel rooms built for a
specific event, which could not be filled later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
