<HEADLINE> Hebron Mayor: Citizens Optimistic About Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of Hebron Municipality
Mostafa al-Natsha said today that citizens in Hebron are upbeat
following the initial of the accord on Israeli troop redeployment
in the West Bank town.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Egyptian Voice of Arab radio, the
mayor said contacts are underway between the Palestinian and
Israeli sides for putting this accord into effect.
</P>
<P>
The issue of Palestinian supervision over the Ibrahimi Mosque,
which had been a sticking point in previous rounds of talks,
remains unsolved and it will be discussed later on, the mayor
said.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord which was initialed Wednesday morning
after a summit between Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, Israel should withdraw
from 80 percent of Hebron within ten days after the signing and
the remaining 20 percent will be negotiated in the future, he
added.
</P>
<P>
About 450 Jewish settlers live among 200,000 Palestinians in
the last West Bank city still under Israeli occupation
</P>
<P>
Under the 1995 Oslo II accords signed by the previous Israeli
Labor government, the Israeli troops pullback from Hebron should
have been completed by the end of March in 1996.
</P>
<P>
But the withdrawal was postponed following a series of suicide
bombings in Israel between February and March in 1996 that killed
over 60 people, and Netanyahu further delayed the pullback on
security reason.  
</P>
</TEXT>
