<HEADLINE> China Issues Outline for Relics Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's impressive Summer
Palace, home of the Qing Dynasty Emperors, heads a list of
cultural relics which China wants to be officially listed as world
heritage sites.
</P>
<P>
China is to ask UNESCO to include another 20 of its historical
sites on the World Cultural Heritage List by 2010, including the
Summer Palace, and a unique ancient town affected by a strong
earthquake in Yunnan Province last year.
</P>
<P>
According to an outline plan for the protection of relics and
museum construction for the coming 15 years, issued today in
Beijing by the State Cultural Relics Bureau, the move is a part of
an ambitious program to preserve the country's 5,000-year-old
civilization.
</P>
<P>
The outline states that in early next century, China will have
2,500 museums, and a huge network to connect thousands of famous
historical sites will be created.
</P>
<P>
"All the historical sites will be protected and utilized in a
scientific, effective and reasonable way," said Zhang Wenbin, head
of the bureau.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that by the year 2000, the central government will
pour an additional 20 million yuan (2.3 million US Dollars) to
protect cultural relics each year, compared with amount allocated
over past five years.
</P>
<P>
Massive investigations will be launched to find out how many
myths still remain in the country, and some 100,000 historical
sites under special protection will be recognized, the outline
reveals.
</P>
<P>
Some key sites will be put under emergency protection, it
added.
</P>
<P>
Archeological work is expected to be stepped up, which will
lead to the conclusion of how Chinese civilization was born, using
high technology to aid the research.
</P>
<P>
The outline revealed that China will send archeologists to do
field work abroad if conditions are right.
</P>
<P>
It urged cultural workers to prevent precious relics from being
shipped abroad, and adopt measures to return smuggled relics to
China.
</P>
<P>
The outline also stressed the importance of museum security and
noted that the country prohibits the auctioning of many rare and
valuable relics.
</P>
<P>
"The central government has always attached great importance to
relics protection and museum construction, because relics are the
symbol of a nation," said Culture Minister Liu Zhongde.
</P>
<P>
The official added that relics protection can help carry
forward the fine tradition of Chinese culture, and spread the
education of patriotism.
</P>
<P>
In China funds for relics protection come from the central
budget.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
