<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Takes Concerted Efforts to Curb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Concerted efforts are being
made in Zimbabwe to minimize air and water pollution in urban
areas by encouraging industrialists to put in place environmental
auditing mechanisms at their factories.
</P>
<P>
This crusade is being spearheaded by the National Cleaner
Production Center (NCPC), which was set up two years ago to fight
industrial pollution.
</P>
<P>
Harare's NCPC Managing Director Lewin Mombemuriwo today said
the idea behind this exercise is to build Zimbabwe's capacity and
improve efficiency in dealing with industrial wastes.
</P>
<P>
He said, "we are looking at technologies which will minimize
the generation of industrial wastes."
</P>
<P>
He added, "the center trains people in companies to do
environmental audits which enable companies which generate waste
to aim for cleaner production."
</P>
<P>
Figures released by UN environment agencies show that in 1995
industrial process emission of carbon dioxide in Zimbabwe reached
16,983 tons, ranking the country seventh largest in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's major contributors to environmental problems
include textile and cotton ginning factories, chemical plants,
petroleum enterprises, paper mills, printing and publishing
houses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
