<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FM: Turkey Respects Territorial Integrity of Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Deputy Prime Minister
and Foreign Minister Tansu Ciller said here today that Turkey
respects territorial integrity of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Ciller made the remarks after her meeting with Iraqi
Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) leader Jalal Talabani, who
arrived here today for the exchange of views with Turkish
officials on the situation in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish foreign minister said that the parties living in
northern Iraq should enjoy their democratic rights and live in
peace, adding that Turkey had launched necessary initiatives to
provide peace in the region after the latest crisis in northern
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
A Peace Monitoring Force (PMF) will soon preserve a ceasefire
declared between Talabani and Iraqi Kurdish Democratic Party
(KDP) head Massoud Barzani on October 31, 1996.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement issued in Ankara Wednesday at the end of
the third round of the talks on the issue of northern Iraq said
that the PMF is likely to be deployed next month.
</P>
<P>
In his part, Talabani said: "We all need democracy but it is
especially necessary for Turkmens and Kurds who suffered a lot
from Iraqi dictatorship."
</P>
<P>
He said that his people did not accept the existence of the
terrorists groups which use the region to stage raids against
Turkey, adding: "we will try to keep Turkey's borders secure as
it is Turkish people's rights to call for border security."
</P>
<P>
The Iran-backed PUK fought with the KDP, supported by
President Saddam Hussein, in late August of last year, which led
to U.S. air strike against Iraqi military targets.
</P>
<P>
The two rival parties signed a peace deal on October 31, 1996
under mediation by the U.S., Britain and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The northern Iraq has been occupied by Kurdish rebels since
the Gulf War in 1991, but it split into rival zones after the
KDP and the PUK began fighting each other in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
