<HEADLINE> WHO: Progress Made in Control of S. American Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The transmission of Chagas
disease has been virtually under full control in Brazil, the World
Health Organization (WHO) said here today.
</P>
<P>
"This important success is a result of control activities
undertaken in the framework of the initiative of the southern cone
countries," said WHO in a press release based on information
provided by the Brazilian national control program. An independent
commission is expected to carry out the ratification of the
interruption of vectorial and transfusional transmission.
</P>
<P>
Chagas disease exists only in the American continent and Brazil
is the biggest endemic country, accounting for over 40 percent of
prevalence of the disease, according to WHO.
</P>
<P>
Chagas disease is a chronic and incurable parasitic disease
which can cause disability and even death. It is estimated that 16
to 18 million Latin Americans have been infected and that 2 to 3
million may have already developed chronic complications.
</P>
<P>
The incurable lesions of Chagas disease develop some 10 to 20
years after the initial acute phase in one-third of those
infected. They include chronic cardiopathy, as well as chronic
digestive lesions and neurological disorders, WHO explained in its
press release.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, the health ministers of Argentina, Bolivia, Brazil,
Chile, Paraguay and Uruguay launched the Southern Cone Initiative
for the Elimination of Transmission of Chagas Disease.
</P>
<P>
Current data on control activities indicate that certification
of the interruption of transmission will be achieved in Chile in
1997, in Brazil in 1998 and in Argentina in 1999. The transmission
was interrupted in Uruguay in 1996. Control activities are
progressing as scheduled in Bolivia and Paraguay, but at this
stage it is not possible to estimate a date for the achievement of
interruption of transmission in those two countries, WHO said.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, only 1,800 insects, which transmit the Chagas disease,
were found by Brazilian national control program field workers in
709,012 homes surveyed, which gives an average of 2.5 insects in
every 1,000 houses, a house infestation rate far below the minimum
threshold necessary to ensure transmission of the parasite to the
dwellers by the vector, WHO said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0018 </DOCNO>
