<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Currency to Remain Stable: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The South African
currency Rand should remain steady in 1997 after nose-diving last
year, the local Standar Bank predicted today.
</P>
<P>
"Unlike last year, an environment characterized by more
positive than negative environmental factors can be expected to
impact on the Rand in 1997," the bank said in a paper.
</P>
<P>
The Rand would depreciate against the U.S. Dollar, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
Rand dropped 29 percent last year, from R3.65 against a dollar
last mid-February to around R4.70 at the end of last December.
The local unit was trading at R4.655 this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the increased competitiveness of the economy,
due to the fall in the Rand last year, and a reduction in imports
would result in significant improvement in the nation's balance
of payments, and ultimately the level of its foreign reserves.
enditem

