<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Inflation Falls to 2.5 Pct in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Britain's annual rate of
inflation fell bigger than expected to 2.5 percent in December, a
drop of 0.2 percent on the previous month, according to figures
released today by the Office for National Statistics (ONS).
</P>
<P>
Economists had expected the headline rate of inflation in
December to fall from 2.7 percent to 2.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The underlying annual rate of inflation, which excludes
mortgage interest payments, fell to 3.1 percent last month from
November's 3.3 percent, its first fall since May last year.
</P>
<P>
The ONS said that lower motoring costs and food prices were
mainly responsible for the fall in the annual inflation rate while
higher housing costs and rise in the price of alcohol put upwards
pressures for the rate of inflation.
</P>
<P>
Both figures were better than economists' forecasts and were
key factors in the government's decision Wednesday not to raise
base interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The figures eased fears about inflationary pressures in
Britain's economy.
</P>
<P>
"These figures show that subdued cost pressures and a stronger
pound are feeding through to lower inflation," Chancellor of the
Exchequer Kenneth Clarke said in a statement after the release of
the data. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
