<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Calls for Optimum Land Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe today said the government's land redistribution exercise
will be meaningless if the land is not put to good use.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a field day held at a farm near Harare, Mugabe
said he wants to see more blacks diversifying into other sectors
of agriculture besides maize farming.
</P>
<P>
"We want to see more blacks going into other sectors of
agriculture such as tobacco, tea, coffee instead of just growing
maize. Why not horticulture and even green beans?" asked Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
He said, "people should learn to be self-reliant, innovative
and hard-working if they are to succeed."
</P>
<P>
Land should be devoted to farming the best suitable crop if
black farmers are to derive the best possible results, Mugabe
noted.
</P>
<P>
He stressed young children in schools should be taught
agriculture as part of their practical subjects to enable them to
appreciate agriculture and know how different crops are grown.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out, "agriculture is the mainstay of the Zimbabwean
economy and farmers should be more thorough if they are to cause
economic growth to rise."
</P>
<P>
He said last year Zimbabwe recorded a 7.8 percent growth rate
and hoped to go further this year by another seven or eight
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
