<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bailey-Johnson Showdown to Take Place in Toronto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The SkyDome of Toronto, Canada,
has been officially declared today the site of the biggest track
showdown of the century, the race between the world's fastest-ever
runners.
</P>
<P>
The announcement that Toronto will host the 150-meter race
between Donovan Bailey of Canada and Michael Johnson of the U.S.
was made today in Canada's largest city of Toronto by Giselle
Briden, the promoter of the One to One Challenge of Champions
meet.
</P>
<P>
"By putting the fastest men ever to run on the same track... we
are creating an event that's going to rock Toronto around the
world," said Briden, president of the Ottawa-based Magellan
Entertainment Group.
</P>
<P>
"This is a great event for track and I'm ready now to confirm
the title of the world's fastest human," said Michael Johnson,
world record holder for the 200 meters and 400 meters, and U.S.
Athlete of the Year for 1996.
</P>
<P>
"Get ready for take-off in Toronto," Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
Donovan Bailey, world record holder for the 100 meters and
Canada's Athlete of the Year for 1996, said that he wanted this
race at home in Canada.
</P>
<P>
"I've said the race would be run on my terms -- the time I
wanted, the location I wanted, and the lane I wanted -- and that's
how it's going to be," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Bailey-Johnson 2-million-dollar race will highlight a
three-hour extravaganza at SkyDome, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
Showcased will be world-class athletic and entertainment
events, including competition between athletes who currently rank
as the world's best in their events.
</P>
<P>
Canada's Bailey set the world record and won the gold medal in
the 100 meters at the Summer Olympic Games in Atlanta, while
Johnson became the first male Olympian to win both the 200- and
400-meter races.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the games, there has been a controversy as to who is
really "the world's fastest man."
</P>
<P>
The Canadians say the title should go to Bailey, while the
Americans insist that Johnson has every reason to be the world's
fastest man.
</P>
<P>
The spring race, dubbed The Challenge of Champions, will be
over 150 meters on a curved track, midway between Bailey's
100-meter event and Johnson's 200.
</P>
<P>
Both men will receive appearance fees of 500,000 dollars, with
the winner taking home another 1 million.
</P>
<P>
"It's really the only way to put two guys together who are
different specialists and make it fair," Johnson said when the
race was announced last November.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's a great opportunity for track and field.... I
think it's a great opportunity for both of us and I look forward
to it," he said at the time.
</P>
<P>
Bailey also welcomed the challenge. "I'm here now, its going to
happen in May so I'm really looking forward to taking on my man
here," he said.
</P>
<P>
Briden confirmed today that final negotiations with corporate
sponsors and broadcast partners are nearing completion, with
announcement to be made in the near future.
</P>
<P>
"Corporate interest in the race is extremely strong and global
in scope," Briden said.
</P>
<P>
"Magellan expects that public demand for tickets will be just
as strong as the interest in sponsorship and broadcast rights,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
She noted that tickets will be priced so that anyone who wants
to go will have an opportunity to enjoy this once-in-a-lifetime
event live. 
</P>
</TEXT>
