<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official: US Opposes Cypriot-Russian Missile Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. official said here today
the United States was opposed to the decision made by the Cyprus
government to purchase S-300 Russian-made missiles.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department official Carey Cavanaugh told reporters
at a press conference that the Cyprus' decision to buy the
surface-to-air missiles with a range of 150 kilometers was a
"mistake", adding that this was not the path towards working on a
peaceful settlement for Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cavanaugh, who arrived here Wednesday afternoon following his
visit to Cyprus and Greece, said that the U.S. is concerned that
this is definitely a setback to international efforts to advance
a settlement to the issue of the divided island of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is able to get the commitment of both the leaders of
the Greek Cypriot and the Turkish Cypriot communities to move
quickly ahead with the implementation of the U.N. package of
proposals to improve the security and safety situation along the
ceasefire lines, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. proposals include adoption of military code of
conduct, extension of the unmanning of army posts along the
demarcation line, removal of land mines and unloading weapons
from the posts near the buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
Cavanaugh held the three-hour talks with Turkish Foreign
Ministry Undersecretary Onur Oymen on the missiles crisis in
Cyprus Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' arms deal with Russia to purchase the anti-aircraft
missiles worth of 250 million U.S. dollars has drawn strong
opposition from the Turkish government and military.
</P>
<P>
On January 10, Turkish Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign
Minister Tansu Ciller threatened Cyprus that Turkey is ready to
strike at Cyprus if its government goes ahead with the arms deal
with Russia.
</P>
<P>
Chief of General Staff of the Turkish Armed Forces Ismail
Hakki Karadayi paid a two-day visit to northern Cyprus between
January 13 and 14 to show Turkey's determination to oppose
Cyprus' deployment of the missiles on the island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides has promised not to deploy
the missiles in the next 16 months
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been partitioned since the Turkish troops landed
on the island in 1974 and seized the northern third of the
island following a short-lived coup seeking union with Greece by
some Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Some 35,000-strong Turkish troops are stationed in northern
Cyprus to protect the Turkish Cypriots on the east Mediterranean
island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
