<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Than 10,000 Swiss Companies Go Bankrupt in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- More than 10,000 companies in
Switzerland declared bankruptcy in 1996, 4.4 percent more than
those in 1995, said the Swiss Credit-Reform Union Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 10,192 companies went into bankruptcy in 1996 while
27,071 new companies registered in the same year, 2.7 percent more
than those in 1995. Of all the new companies, 50 percent are in
the service sector, 22.5 percent in wholesale business and 20
percent in construction, according to the union.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, annexation and transaction of companies were active. A
total of 345 companies were involved. Two chemical plants, Chiba
and Sandoz, were merged into Novartis, a new international
enterprise said to be the biggest in the chemical world. Several
Swiss companies were purchased by foreign companies like Germany's
Siemens and the U.S. Baxter.
</P>
<P>
However, Swiss companies also bought a dozen of foreign
companies in 1996. The Swiss Reassurances bought Mercantile and
GeneralRe for 3.015 billion Swiss francs (about 2.2 billion U.S.
dollars), becoming the world's largest reassurances company.
Switzerland's ABB acquired 10 foreign companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
