<HEADLINE>   Cyprus, Russia to Sign Economic Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- A Cyprus government official
announced here today that Cyprus and Russia will sign an
agreement on mutual promotion and protection of investments in
the Caucasian region of Krasnodar.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus Finance Minister Christodoulos Christodoulou made the
announcement after a meeting with Russian Ambassador to Cyprus
Georgi Muratov on furthering bilateral economic ties.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot minister will visit Russia in April to hold talks
with Russian officials and sign the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Christodoulou said preparations have already been made for
the signing of the agreement, adding that the European Bank of
Development and Reconstruction will cooperate on the matter.
</P>
<P>
The Russian ambassador noted that cooperation between Cyprus
and Russia on trade and economic matters is progressing "very
positively" with possibilities for further cooperation, covering
not only the Aegean, but the Black Sea region as well which is
historically and culturally linked to Hellenism.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Cyprus' acquisition of Russian S-300
surface-to-air missiles, the Russian ambassador said the contract
for their sale will be kept, but avoided commenting on
U.S. official Carey Cavanaugh's statement made Wednesday that the
missiles will not finally be installed on the island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' deal to buy Russian missiles with a range of 150
kilometers, which was signed on January 4, has triggered
criticism from the United States. And Turkey has threatened to
strike at the missiles if they are deployed.
</P>
<P>
However, the Cyprus government has vowed to go ahead with the
deal despite the Turkish threats.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has purchased some advanced tanks and armoured vehicles
from Russia for the past few years despite opposition from the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been partitioned since the Turkish troops landed on
the island in 1974 and seized the northern third of the island
following a short-lived coup by some Greek Cypriots seeking union
with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Some 35,000 strong Turkish troops are stationed in northern
Cyprus to protect the Turkish Cypriots on the east Mediterranean
island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
