<HEADLINE> Britain's Clarke Leaves Base Rates on Hold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Chancellor of the
Exchequer Kenneth Clarke left interest rates on hold today
following his monthly monetary meeting Wednesday with Bank of
England governor Eddie George.
</P>
<P>
City economists had expected Clarke to leave base rates at
their current level of 6 percent, which was reached at the end of
last October when they rose one quarter of a point.
</P>
<P>
Britain's central bank, the Bank of England, has recently kept
on pressing for an increase in interest rates on fear of the
economy's overheating.
</P>
<P>
However, Clarke said that although the strong pound distorted
Britain's trade with other countries, it helped to counter
inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
"The big thing at the moment is the pound is very strong and
that is very anti-inflationary," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the pound had risen 15 percent in the last year
overall, and was up 20 percent versus the mark.
</P>
<P>
The stock market welcomed the news, with the FTSE 100 resuming
its recent record run, and by mid-afternoon it was more than 30
points up at 4,191.7. 
</P>
</TEXT>
