<HEADLINE> Food Poisoning Outbreak Claims 17th Life in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 16 (Xinhua) -- A 17th person has died in the
E-coli food poisoning outbreak in Scotland, taking the total death
toll to 17, according to Scottish health officials.
</P>
<P>
The latest victim was an elderly woman who was a resident of
Bankview nursing home near Edinburgh and she had been ill since
the outbreak started last November.
</P>
<P>
She is also the sixth person to die in the Forth Valley Health
Board area and the fourth person at the nursing home to have
succumbed to the bacteria.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that almost 400 people have reported symptoms
of the food poisoning, which can cause kidney failure in
vulnerable people such as the elderly and young children.
</P>
<P>
The British government, which ordered emergency research into
the causes of E-coli Wednesday, said that it would check whether
food handling and licensing laws needed tightening.
</P>
<P>
According to medical experts, E-coli is a bacteria normally
found in the guts of cattle, sheep and people. It is usually
harmless, but a toxic strain that lives in cattle can be passed to
human via manure or improper slaughtering. 
</P>
</TEXT>
