<HEADLINE> Lebanon Fears Mounting Israeli Pressure on Lebanon and Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Elias Hrawi
repeated here today a fear that Israel would exert more pressure
on both Lebanon and Syria after reaching an agreement with the
Palestinian leadership on a redeployment in the West Bank town
of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Lebanese National News Agency(LNNA) reported
that the president expressed the fear in meetings with
parliamentary deputies in the Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
"President Elias Hrawi reiterated his fear of mounting
Israeli pressures on Lebanon and Syria, in the wake of the
Hebron agreement," the official LNNA said in its evening news
bulletin.
</P>
<P>
The president "expressed apprehensions that Israel could
utilize security incidents taking place in various areas in
Lebanon, but he ruled out a large-scale (Israeli) military
operation reaching the degree of devastation," according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement which the Israelis and the Palestinians
initialed earlier Wednesday, Israel will hand over most of
Hebron to the Palistinians, in the first concrete move in the
peace process since Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu
took power in June.
</P>
<P>
During a cabinet meeting, the president said that the
agreement "does not necessarily mean Israel has changed its
negative stance on the peace process in the region."
</P>
<P>
He urged the country's security forces to "keep eyes wide
open and carry out full responsibility within the law in order
to safeguard public security throughout the country."
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz
received in his office this afternoon Ron Schlycher, charge
d'affairs of the United States in Beirut, and discussed with
him the Palestinian-Israeli agreement on Hebron.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the two-and-half-a-hour meeting, the
U.S. diplomat announced that he conveyed to the Lebanese foreign
minister the U.S. hope that the agreement would draw "more
progresses not only on the Israeli-Palestinian track, but also
on both the Lebanese and Syrian tracks."
</P>
<P>
Schlycher underlined that the Washington administration would
continue to follow the policy in the Middle East which is "aimed
at the achievement of a comprehensive, just and lasting peace,"
and he ruled out the eruption of a war in the region.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks of Syria and Lebanon with the Jewish state has
deadlocked since last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
