<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-16 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy to Visit Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General's
special envoy for Cyprus Han sung Joo will be here soon in a bid to
start direct negotiations between the two rival Greek and Turkish
communities on the island, a U.N. official announced today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting with President Glafcos Clerides in
Presidential Palace, U.N. Secretary-General's resident
representative in Cyprus Gustave Feissel said Han's week-long
visit at the end of this month aims at "trying to move the process
forward in a year described as good for Cyprus".
</P>
<P>
The visit is part of U.N. intensified effort to prepare
the ground for direct talks as soon as possible, Feissel said,
adding that there are "time restraints" in the U.N. effort,
such as the presidential elections in February next year and
Cyprus' accession negotiations with the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the ongoing military dialogue between the
National guard and the Turkish forces, Feissel appeared optimistic
that an agreement on the U.N. measures is imminent.
</P>
<P>
"I hope as discussions continue in the coming days and
week that we are going to see some dramatic change in what
we hear on both sides," Feissel said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the U.N. has made it clear to both that
agreement must be reached on the entire package of measures
and not just on one of the three proposals under discussion,
which include the extension of the unmanning to cover the
length of the demarcation line, the removal of loaded weapons
and a code of conduct.
</P>
<P>
The U.N., he added, has also warned both sides that if
they continue to insist on agreement on a specific item, this
would be tantamount to a rejection of the measures and refusal
to discuss them.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that Han' upcoming visit follows a
tension on the island after Cyprus' acquisition of Russian-made
S-300 surface-to-air missiles.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has threatened to strike at the missiles if they
are deployed.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed and seized the northern third of the island following
a pro-Athens coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
