<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus President Leaves for Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides left here today for Athens for talks with his Greek
counterpart Costis Stephanopoulos and Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, which will also be attended by the
foreign and defense ministers of the two countries, the Cyprus
problem as well as the joint defense pact, agreed upon by
the governments of Cyprus and Greece in November 1993, will be
discussed, official sources here said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before his departure from Larnaca
Airport, President Clerides reffered to Cyprus' deal to buy
Russian missiles, saying that the 16-month period between the
purchase and the installation of the Russian S-300 anti-aircraft
missiles gives ample time to the U.S. to launch their
initiative to assist efforts for a Cyprus settlement.
</P>
<P>
concerning the U.S.-proposed moratorium on overflights of Greek
and Turkish military aircraft in Cyprus, President Clerides said
the issue will also be discussed during his meetings in
Athens.
</P>
<P>
He said that overflights of Greek aircraft are part of
the defense agreement concluded between Cyprus and Greece and
therefore a decision on the moratorium should be "a decision
of both governments".
</P>
<P>
"During a period of political detente, as for example when
negotiations are in progress, we could refrain from scheduling
overflights," the President said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the process of the ongoing military dialogue
between the National Guard and the Turkish forces under U.N.
auspices, President Clerides reaffirmed the government's readiness
to discuss all issues proposed by U.N. Security Council
resolution 1092, adopted in 1996.
</P>
<P>
These include the adoption of a code of conduct,
prohibiting loaded weapons along the ceasefire lines and extension
of the 1989 unmanning agreement to other areas where the two
sides remain in close proximity to each other.
</P>
<P>
Early today, government spokesman Yiannakis Cassoulides said
that President Clerides' talks in Athens will be conducted on
the basis of a document prepared by high ranking Greek
government officials with a paper President Clerides had already
prepared on the current situation.
</P>
<P>
"What is important is the actual talks and the exchange
of views and ideas about future moves in the efforts for a
political settlement in Cyprus," the spokesman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
President Clerides' current visit to Greece follows a tension
on this east Mediterranean island after Cyprus government's
decision to buy Russian-made surface-to-air missiles.
</P>
<P>
The deal to buy the missiles with a range of 150
kilometers, signed on January 4, has triggered criticism from
the United States and some other countries. And Turkey has
threatened to strike at the missiles if they are deployed.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and seized 37 per cent of the island following a
short-lived coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Athens has warned Ankara that any further advance of the
Turkish troops toward the Greek Cypriot-controlled southern part
of the island would mean war between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
