<HEADLINE> Luxemburg's Foreign Minister Arrives in Beirut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Luxemburg's Foreign Minister
Jacques Poos arrived in Beirut from Damascus this evening to
explore Europe's role in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Poos, received at the airport by his Lebanese counterpart
Farez Boueiz, came before his country taking the rotating
chairmanhood of the European Community in February.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to have official talks with Boueiz Friday
morning, which will be followed by meetings with Lebanese
President Elias Hrawi, House Speaker Nabih Berri and Prime
Minister Rafik Hariri.
</P>
<P>
At the Beirut International Airport, Poos announced that he
would get a knowledge from the Lebanese government its position
on an agreement initialed by the Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators Wednesday on the problem of West Bank town of
Hebron.
</P>
<P>
He said that his talks with the Lebanese leaders would also
deal with a Euro-Mediterranean dialogue in light of an upcoming
conference of the European and Mediterranean countries on
ministerial level.
</P>
<P>
Poos pointed out that his mission in the Middle East, which
started in a "pessimistic" atmosphere, has "changed and
improved" after the signature of the Hebron agreement between
the Israeli and Palestinian leaders.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, under which Israel will hand over most of
Hebron to the Palestinian National Authority of Yasir Arafat, is
the first concrete step taken by Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
 Netanyahu since he took power last June.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese Foreign Minister, on the other hand, spoke
highly of Europe's concern over the situations in the region in
general and in Lebanon in particular.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming Poos' visit to Lebanon, Boueiz noted that this was
the Luxemburg foreign minister's first visit to this country,
and one by a senior official from a "friend country of Lebanon."
</P>
<P>
He said that the Lebanese government considered "positive"
the statements which have been issued by the European Community
on the Middle East peace process. 
</P>
