<HEADLINE> First Divorce Case in Irish Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 16 (Xinhua) -- A High Court judge in Dublin
heard the first divorce case to come before the Irish courts
Wednesday, according to a report from the Irish capital today.
</P>
<P>
Divorce in Ireland was approved in a referendum in November
1995, but the new Divorce Act does not come into effect until
February 27.
</P>
<P>
The case was brought by a man in his 50s who is terminally ill
and wishes to marry again before he dies.
</P>
<P>
The hearing was held in secret to protect the identities of the
man, his wife and the woman with whom he has lived for several
years.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that his wife did not oppose the declaration.
And the man also asked for the three months' notice for an
intended marriage to be waived.
</P>
<P>
The divorce referendum in Ireland divided the Irish Republic.
Following a 0.56 percent margin of victory for the "Yes" camp,
there were legal challenges in the Irish High Court and Supreme
Court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
