<HEADLINE> Gulf Air Forced to sell planes, Close Routes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Bahrain-based Gulf Air
has decided to sell six Boeing-767 aircraft and close routes in a
bid to save itself from falling into a debt trap, the official
Bahraini News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after a recent meeting by the Board of
the airline, which is equally owned by Qatar, Oman, Bahrain, and
the United Arab Emirates (UAE), the executive chairman of the
Gulf Air Sheikh Ahammed bin Suaef al Nahyan said in a statement
to the Bahraini News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The regional carrier will sell six planes during the period
from February to July and close some uneconomic routes to help
reduce its debt burden and realize profits, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The routes which will be closed include its flights to and
from New York, Geneva and Johanesburg.
</P>
<P>
The carrier has mapped out measures to prevent travelers from
being affected, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf Air's debts are estimated at some 2 billion
U.S. dollars, mostly in bank loans. The debts resulted from a
flurry of buying new aircraft in the late 1980s and opening
uneconomic routes.
</P>
<P>
The debt-ridden carrier currently has 32 aircraft, said to be
far more than its needs to fly a handful of its profitable routes.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the airline recorded its worst annual loss of 159
million dollars, the biggest since the Gulf crisis in
1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
