<HEADLINE> E. Africa Plans to Form Single Tourism Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Government tourism
sectors of East African Cooperation (EAC) states have endorsed a
proposal on a study to liberalize the tourism industry toward
establishing a single market in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
The endorsement was reached at a two-day EAC meeting, attended
by 16 delegates from three EAC member countries, Kenya, Uganda
and Tanzania, which ended here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting noted with concern the need to facilitate a free
flow of tourists to boost the market.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued here today, the delegates
recommended that the terms of reference of the study would
include the need for equitable sharing of benefits among member
states.
</P>
<P>
Other terms of reference include the type of the tourism
products, logistical support, environmental impact and the number
of tourists visiting the region compared to global figures.
</P>
<P>
The study would also address the removal of restrictions such
as border crossing obstacles and unnecessary administrative
requirements.
</P>
<P>
The delegates also recommended harmonization of the member
states' tourism policies including a review of the 1985 Tourism
Agreement between Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The proposal of the study was presented to the meeting by the
EAC secretariat which is in charge of facilitating regional
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
It would also seek way of promoting an overall marketing plan
and strategy that would form the basis for a more detailed study
of an action plan to be agreed upon by the three member states.
</P>
<P>
A special committee was formed during the meeting for the
purpose of updating their policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
