<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today met with Sudanese Vice-President El Zubeir Mohamed Saleh who
arrived here unexpectedly Wednesday as his country mobilized for
conflict againist advancing rebels.
</P>
<P>
In a two-paragraph story, the Egyptian MENA news agency gave no
details about the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Saleh made the unannounced visit amid escalating tensions in
Sudan as government forces are fighting against rebels in areas
bordering Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
It is learned here that the Sudanese official, who returned to
Khartoum, had conveyed a message from Sudanese President Omar
Hassan al-Bashir to Mubarak, which explains the latest development
on the country's eastern border.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two sides stressed the importance to
dispel the tense atmosphere that hurts the bilateral ties and
normalize the diplomatic relationship, Saleh told reporters upon
his return to Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
He said Egypt underlined the importance to maintain Sudan's
sovereignty and expressed support to this end.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Sadek al Mahdi, leader of Sudan's
largest opposition Umma Party, left here for Riyadh on Wednesday
evening, winding up a fortnight's visit to Egypt within the
context of his multi-leg tour of Arab, Gulf and European countries.
</P>
<P>
Cairo-Khartoum ties have been cool since Egypt accused Sudan of
having orchestrated the 1995 failed attempt on the life of the
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in Addis Ababa and granting
asylum to Egyptian extremists.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese troops and rebel forces have been engaged in a
military clash since Sunday after two towns on the border with
Ethiopia were attacked by rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
While the Arab League has expressed "deep worries" over the
Sudanese situation, Egypt has given no response so far.
</P>
<P>
Sudan's opposition forces comprise elements from the Umma
Party, the Democratic Unionist Party, the Sudanese Democratic
Alliance and the Sudan People's Liberation Army. 
</P>
