<HEADLINE> U.S. Regulators to Study Boeing-McDonnell Douglas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 16 (Xinhua) --The U.S Federal Trade
Commission (FTC) is going to study the big merger between Boeing
Co. and McDonnell Douglas Corp., Attorney General Janet Reno said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Both the FTC and the U.S. Justice Department's antitrust
division have jurisdiction to review mergers.
</P>
<P>
Seattle-based Boeing said last month it would pay 13.34 billion
U.S. dollars in stock for McDonnell Douglas, based in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
The merger would produce a civilian- and military-aircraft
giant with projected annual revenues of 48 billion dollars, and
hence the world's largest aerospace company. It would be able to
grab 65 percent of the world jetliner market, almost double the
share of its only rival, Europe's Airbus Industrie consortium.
</P>
<P>
European Union antitrust regulators also have announced they
intend to review the Boeing-MD merger to ensure it in line with
the 15-member trade bloc's rules. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Chief: Hebron Deal Just First Step </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary
General Esmat Abdul-Meguid said today the Hebron deal initialed by
the Palestinians and the Israelis Wednesday was "the first step
along the road of fostering aspiration for confidence."
</P>
<P>
In a press release here, the AL chief urged follow-up steps to
build on the momentum and confidence inspired by the Hebron deal .
</P>
<P>
The accord should be followed by urgent steps on other
negotiation tracks so as to achieve full Israeli withdrawal from
the occupied Arab territories in accordance with the international
laws, U.N. resolutions and the land for peace principle, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Abdul-Meguid said in the press release the efforts of Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak and King Hussein of Jordan for reaching
the accord fall within the resolutions of the Pan-Arab summit held
here in June which underlined that just and comprehensive peace is
the strategic option of the Arab nations.
</P>
<P>
He urged the United States and the European Union to resume
diplomatic efforts to boost the peace process along all tracks
until just and comprehensive peace is realized in the Middle
East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
