<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang People Fight Snow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-six people have been
killed and 18 others have been seriously injured by a heavy snow
in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Four people are still missing. Since an unprecedented snowstorm
hit Xinjiang in late December, the number of people affected by
the snow has surpassed 320,000, mostly with people cut off or
trapped.
</P>
<P>
The snow has also damaged 183,800 houses belonging to herdsmen.
</P>
<P>
Twenty three counties in seven prefectures in the region have
been stricken by the worst snowfall for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
The snow is up to two meters deep in the mountain areas and 40
centimeters deep in the plain areas. Successive snowstorms and
avalanches have killed people, blocked roads and cut off
telecommunications lines and power supplies.
</P>
<P>
Direct economic losses caused by the disaster have reached 247
million yuan (about 29.8 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
People in the region, led by the Chinese Communist Party and
the local government have worked all out in a massive relief
operation.
</P>
<P>
The Xinjiang regional government has organized emergency relief
operations. By January 16, helicopters had flown 34 sorties,
rescuing 310 herdsmen, geological surveyors, gold miners and
border guards.
</P>
<P>
More than 10 tons of food and medicine have been air dropped to
snow trapped herdsmen.
</P>
<P>
The Xinjiang Military Area Command has sent 1,000 tons of
materials to grasslands in southern part of the region by road,
saving 12,000 herdsmen and 337,000 farm animals from hunger.
</P>
<P>
The regional government has also extended 16 million yuan in
loans and granted three million yuan's worth of relief funding for
the resumption of industrial production in the snow-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
Relief funding of 14 million yuan and 2,500 tons of firewood
and fuel have also been sent to the victims.
</P>
<P>
So far tens of thousands of people have joined the relief
teams. Aid materials are pouring into the disaster-stricken
areas. About 23 million kg of fodder and 250 million kg of feeding
grass have already arrived in the snow-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
More than 30,000 snow trapped people, 540 automobiles and
200,000 farm animals have been rescued and transferred to safe
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
