<HEADLINE> Iraqi Oil Expected to Flow Into Philippine Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi oil may soon flow into the
Philippine market as the two countries are expected to enter a
deal under the United Nations (UN) scheme of oil for food,
Philippine Foreign Affairs Secretary Domingo Siazon said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Siazon made this remark after attending a 30-minute meeting in
the Presidential Palace between President Fidel Ramos and visiting
Speaker Saadoun Hamadi of the National Assembly of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said the six-member parliamentarian delegation from Iraq are
in the country to sell oil, which would be used to purchase
Philippine food and medicines for Iraqi nationals, particularly
women and children.
</P>
<P>
The expected inflow of Iraqi oil will probably cushion the
impact of the on-going oil price increases in the Philippines,
which today witnessed another 3.3 percent hike for oil price per
liter, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Hamadi also relayed President Saddam
Hussein's appreciation for the participation of the Philippines in
the UN scheme which will enable Iraq to import foods and medicines
in exchange for Iraqi oil.
</P>
<P>
The export of local food products, medicines, and
pharmaceuticals to Iraq will be undertaken by the Philippine
International Trading Corporation, which is targeting 20-30
percent of the two-billion U.S. worth of oil Iraq is allowed to
export every six months.
</P>
<P>
The UN imposed the trade embargo on Iraq following the
country's invasion of Kuwait in 1990. It allowed Iraq to begin
selling oil for food last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
