<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB, Donors to Replenish Soft Loan Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
and donors have agreed to replenish the bank's soft loan fund, the
Asian Development Fund (ADF), with 6.3 billion U.S. dollars, the
Manila-based bank announced today.
</P>
<P>
The bank said in a statement that the agreement was reached at
the seventh and the final donors' meeting which concluded in Tokyo
today, with the donors agreeing that the ADF should remain as a
single fund.
</P>
<P>
The ADF loans are provided on concessionary terms to the
poorest of the ADB's developing members. The typically
interest-free loans have repayment periods of at least 30 years
and carry a service charge of one percent annually.
</P>
<P>
The previous replenishment was 6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the donors agreed to contribute up to 3
billion dollars while the ADB, for the first time, would provide
more than half of the replenishment, which will cover a four-year
period from 1997 to 2000.
</P>
<P>
It also said that Japan remains the largest contributor with
1.019 billion dollars, followed by the United States and the
European donors.
</P>
<P>
Another major achievement of the Tokyo meeting was that donor
countries in the Asia Pacific region have agreed to increase their
share of contributions to 50 percent of the fund, the statement
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
