<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Nuclear Output in 1996 Exceeds 14 Billion Kwh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- China's nuclear power output
reached 14.3 billion kilowatt hours (kwh) in 1996, a 12 percent
rise over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The Qinshan Nuclear Power Plant in east China's Zhejiang
Province generated 2.23 billion kwh, while the Daya Bay Plant in
southern Guangdong Province produced 12.11 billion kwh.
</P>
<P>
A conference of the China National Nuclear Corporation (CNNC),
which concluded in Beijing today, was told by a company official
that last year the utilization rate of generating units at the
Qinshan and Daya Bay plants reached 86.4 percent and 72.6 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The rates were described as good compared to the average rate
of 81.3 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, China's output of nuclear power accounted for just one
percent of the country's total power output.
</P>
<P>
The official said that China's nuclear power sector should
increase its proportion of the country's power structure, in which
thermal power accounts for 75 percent and hydropower, 24
percent.
</P>
<P>
He said burning of coal for the development of thermal power
will further burden the country's transport system and continue to
worsen the environment.
</P>
<P>
China's hydroelectrical resources, however, are mainly
distributed in southwest, restricting the development of
hydropower.
</P>
<P>
In the longer perspective, the official said, "China must boost
nuclear power for its economic construction."
</P>
<P>
China plans to build four new nuclear power plants with a total
generating capacity of 6.9 million kilowatts in Lianyungang,
Qinshan and Daya Bay.
</P>
<P>
The official predicted that China's nuclear industry will not
take off until the next century. The country's nuclear generating
capacity will rise from current 2.1 million kw to 20 million kw by
2010. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finland Tops World in Per-Capita Possession of Mobile Phones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Seven in every 25 people in
Finland now have a mobile phone, giving the country the highest
density of cellular phones per person in the world.
</P>
<P>
So far, the number of mobile phones in Finland has reached more
than 1.5 million and new subscribers are still increasing at a
rate of 50,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that some 500,000 new mobile phones were sold
in Finland last year, and the country is expected to see around
600,000 new subscribers this year.
</P>
<P>
Finland was one of the first countries to set up national
mobile phone networks in the 1970s. It also participated in the
establishment of the first international mobile phone network
among Nordic countries in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
As the most advanced digital GSM network has been introduced to
the country since 1990, Finland saw a boost in mobile phone sales,
which were further pushed by the invention of more exquisite
phones and continuously declining prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
