<HEADLINE> &AMP;0 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today hosted the ceremonial inauguration of 10 Japan-funded
bridges constructed in Mindanao in the southern part of the
country.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony held in the Presidential Palace here, Ramos
said the bridges would significantly boost trade, commerce,
transportation, travel and tourism in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The bridges, constructed with a Japanese grant worth 873
million pesos (33 million U.S. dollars), were part of the 234
bridges to be built under a five-year program aided by Japan.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the bridges would help promote the economic
development in Mindanao, where a peace agreement was signed
between the Moro National Liberation Front and the government last
September ending a 24-year-old war.
</P>
<P>
The bridges would also facilitate the further integration of
the heretofore isolated communities in Mindanao with the rest part
of the country, said Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Ambassador to the Philippines Hiroyuki Yushita
attended the inauguration ceremony.  
</P>
</TEXT>
