<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tory Lawmaker's Death Raises Doubts Over Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The death of a Tory backbencher
on Thursday pushed the Conservative government into a minority in
the British parliament, raising doubts over whether Prime Minister
John Major could have the general election in May as planned.
</P>
<P>
The death of Iain Mills leaves the Tories with 322
parliamentary seats and the combined Opposition parties with 323,
excluding the Speaker and her three deputies, who usually do not
vote.
</P>
<P>
Labor has been seeking to unite the opposition parties since
late last year to secure passage of a no-confidence vote against
the government, which could force Major to call an early election.
</P>
<P>
Under the British law, the prime minister could choose the date
of the polls, which must be be held by May 22.
</P>
<P>
However, the Labor Party said it could hardly win the
tug-of-war because the Ulster Unionists, who hold the linchpin
votes in the House of Commons, do not seem to be considering
stopping support for Major.
</P>
<P>
To get a vote of censure through the parliament, Labor would
have to secure all the votes of the opposition, including all its
MPs and every member of the other opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
The Ulster Unionists said they had no plan to withdraw their
support for the ruling party, which allows a Conservative majority
in all legislative committees.
</P>
<P>
A senior Labor official said the death of Mills is little more
than a psychological blow to the Tories and would not make much
difference in the election timetable.
</P>
<P>
Although Tories said that May was still the favored option for
the election, there are signs of a quickened pace of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
The sudden burst of activity included the rescheduling of the
Welsh conference and a new arrangement of political broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
Tory headquarters said that this is just an effort of the Major
government to focus attention on the main election issues, such as
tax. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
