<HEADLINE> EU, France Deny Report on Common Income Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The European Union Thursday
denied a British report that some countries led by Germany and
France were planning to impose a common income tax in the
single-currency countries.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the European Commission (EC) were quoted as saying
that the EU treaties leave income tax exclusive under the control
of the countries' treasuries, giving Brussels a say merely over
certain indirect taxes like value-added tax.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, French European Affairs Minister Michel Barnier
dismissed the report by the London-based newspaper "The
Independent" as a reflection of Britain's pre-electoral worry over
the European policy.
</P>
<P>
He said that he had "never heard of" anything about common
income tax during negotiations on the European monetary policy.
</P>
