<HEADLINE> Crackdown on Drug Crimes Fruitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- China's nationwide crackdown on
drug crime proved fruitful last year, with the country's police
cracking 87,000 drug-related cases.
</P>
<P>
Officers confiscated 4,000 kilograms of heroin, 1,700 kg of
opium, and 1,000 kg of "ice", worth millions of yuan at street
prices.
</P>
<P>
About 110,000 people were found to be involved in drug related
crimes, according to sources at a national conference of the State
Anti-Narcotics Committee held today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the results provided a good springboard for the
country's anti-narcotics work in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
The number of illegal drug users in China has continued to
increase in recent years, and drug-related crime has done great
harm to the country's social stability.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the conference urged governments and CPC party
committees at all levels to do their best in the country's
anti-narcotics campaigns, and to impose compulsory rehabilitation
programs on illegal drug users.
</P>
<P>
China's public security organs were also urged to take more
effective steps to combat drug crime at the conference, and for
tough sentences to be handed out to drug traffickers and dealers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, governments at all levels should also take measures
to improve rules and regulations, and management of narcotics, and
make precautionary measures to improve social order.
</P>
<P>
Tao Siju, Minister of Public Security and director of the State
Anti-Narcotics Committee, and Xiang Jingfu, deputy director of the
committee, attended the meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
