<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon: Hebron Agreement Not End to Talks Between </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz warned here today against considering an agreement on
Israeli troops redeployment in the West Bank town of Hebron as an
end to the peace talks between the Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"The Hebron agreement should not be considered as tantamount
to an end of the Palestinian track in order to conceal
other rights of the Palestinians," Boueiz said in a press
conference held jointly with visiting Foreign Minister of
Luxemburg Jacques Poos.
</P>
<P>
Israel's Parliament voted Thursday and approved the agreement
on Hebron, which was initialed by the Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators Wednesday, thereby giving the green light for Israeli
soldiers to pull out of 80 percent of the West Bank town.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese foreign minister maintained that the Hebron
accord failed to give the Palestinians their full rights, noting that
the area obtained by the Palestinians in the agreement "is less
than all the Hebron area."
</P>
<P>
"Secondly, the authority to be exercised by the Palestinians
in Hebron is less than the authority which the Palestinians
should exercise," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Thirdly, Israel preserves its presence (in Hebron), the
principle of joint patrols and the principle of chasing
Palestinians in the area," the Lebanese minister added.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Israel will not hand over 20 percent
of Hebron, where some 400 Jewish settlers are allowed to
live.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that this agreement will not actually conceal
rights of the Palestinians as we have seen," Boueiz said.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped that the agreement "will not be the last and
final pay for what we consider rights of the Palestinians, the
most basical of which are the right of self-determination and the
right of establishing an independent state," Boueiz said.
</P>
<P>
"All the information we have got until now forced us to say
that this agreement should not be considered an end of the
Palestinian file," he said, "because we are afraid that the
Israeli government would believe what it has given now is enough
and constitutes a last pay for the Palestinian rights."
</P>
<P>
Poos said that his talks with Boueiz dealt with the last
developments of the Middle East peace process, the general
situation in the region as well as the relations between
Syria and Lebanon on one hand and Israel on the other.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Hebron agreement should be considered
as a "step forward in a process which will be long and in
which there are still other issues yet to be solved and
more difficult than the problem of the West Bank."
</P>
<P>
Poos said that the agreement constituted a "stage which
should be followed by other stages" rather than a final
point in the peace talks between the Palestinians and the
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
The Luxemburg foreign minister arrived in Beirut from Damascus
Thursday evening. Today, he also held meetings with Lebanese
President Elias Hrawi and Prime Minister Rafik Hariri. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
