<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Labor Earns More In Third Quarter of 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The average earnings of Hong
Kong labor increased by three percent in real terms in the third
quarter of 1996 over a year earlier, as shown by the latest
government statistics.
</P>
<P>
The average labor earnings in all major sectors, as measured by
payroll per person engaged, rose by 8.6 percent in nominal terms,
the Census and Statistics Department said today.
</P>
<P>
Payroll in the wholesale, retail, import and export trade,
restaurant and hotel sectors recorded the fastest real growth of
5.2 percent in the third quarter of 1996 compared with the same
period of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Workers in services, finance, insurance, real estate,
transport, storage and telecommunications sectors also earned more
money after discounting the inflation effect, while the real
incomes of workers in manufacturing sectors declined slightly.
</P>
<P>
The overall wage index for September 1996 rose by 6.4 percent
in nominal terms or 1.2 percent in real terms over a year earlier.
The faster increase in earnings over wages was due to more
overtime pay and the issue of irregular payments, said a
government spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Average payroll includes wages and all other irregular
receipts, such as bonuses and overtime payments. Statistics on
average payroll tend to show larger quarter-to-quarter changes,
affected by the length of working hours and the timing of payment
of bonuses and back-pay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
