<HEADLINE> HK-based Dragonair Orders Additional Jet From Airbus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong-based Dragonair has
 ordered an additional A330-300 aircraft from Airbus Industrie,
bringing its total commitments to the advanced widebody twinjets
to six, a press release said today.
</P>
<P>
The new A330, to be delivered in the fourth quarter of 1998,
will join an existing all-Airbus Industrie fleet serving
Dragonair's regional route network, which now includes 24
destinations in the Chinese mainland and across Asia.
</P>
<P>
Dragonair currently operates a fleet of seven single-aisle
A320s and four A330s, and announced in October 1996 that it had
ordered two additional A320s, with options on five more. The
airline also confirmed the lease of another A330, which will enter
its fleet in mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
The new aircraft will enable Dragonair to increase capacity on
existing routes and to open new routes.
</P>
<P>
The airline's Chief Operating Officer, Philip Chen, said,
"Dragonair operates one of the youngest and most advanced aircraft
fleets in the world, and the addition of new aircraft like the
A330 demonstrates our confidence in the future, and our commitment
to providing our passengers with the highest standards of comfort
and service."
</P>
<P>
Dragonair received its first A330 in May 1995 and operates the
type on high-density routes linking Hong Kong with Beijing,
Shanghai, Xiamen and Kaohsiung.  
</P>
