<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Hero On Screen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- A film which tells the story of
one man's fight against lawless hunters of China's threatened
wildlife has won an award.
</P>
<P>
China's Ministry of Forestry today conferred the first
"Forestry Culture Award" to the newly-made film on the Tibetan who
devoted his life to the protection of rare animals.
</P>
<P>
"Gyalsang Soinam Daje" is the name of the film based on a true
story. Gyalsang, 40, died in a fierce gun fight with 18 illegal
hunters in an unpopulated area in west China's Qinghai Province on
January 18, 1994.
</P>
<P>
The zone, 5,300 meters above sea level, and with the lowest
temperatures reaching minus 50 degrees Centigrade, is home to a
large number of rare animals, such as the Tibetan Antelope and
argali sheep.
</P>
<P>
It also attracts many hunters who show no concern for the laws
protecting wild animals.
</P>
<P>
Gyalsang, deputy secretary of the Zhiduo county committee of
the Chinese Communist Party, had been to the zone 12 times,
traveling over 60,000 kilometers in a drive to crack down on the
law breakers.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Forestry and the State Bureau of Environmental
Protection conferred on the brave official the title "Environment
Guard".
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the World Commission on Environment and
Development extended heartfelt condolences at the time of
Gyalsang's death.
</P>
<P>
"The film is the best way to commemorate this heroic man," said
Xu Youfang, Minister of Forestry at today's premiere of the film.
</P>
<P>
"Gyalsang proved that protecting wild animals is a hard course,
paying with his blood and life, but at the same time he has
aroused the public's attention to the work," commented Xu.
</P>
<P>
The minister called on society to take action to help in the
protection of rare wild animals and plants.
</P>
<P>
China has set up 574 natural reserves, with 69 designated by
the State Council as state-level reserves, according to government
statistics.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Forestry has launched rescue projects to save
animals on the verge of extinction, such as the giant panda.
</P>
<P>
The "Forestry Culture Award" was established to encourage
artists to contribute to protection work, he explained.
</P>
<P>
To finish the film, the production group visited the hinterland
of the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau three times, carrying their equipment
to places over 4,000 meters above sea level, and spending over 120
days in the poverty-stricken area, according to starring actor Guo
Bichuan, who plays Gyalsang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
