<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Retain Consulate General in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia will retain its
consulate general in Hong Kong after the British colony's transfer
to the People's Republic of China on midnight June 30 this year,
chief spokesman of the Foreign Ministry Ghaffar Fadyl said here
today.
</P>
<P>
"All Indonesian interests in Hong Kong, such as trade,
immigration and consular activities, will remain in operation," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that all matters related to Indonesian interests in
Hong Kong were discussed by the governments of Indonesia and China
and that Jakarta has decided not to make any change.
</P>
<P>
He added that the presence of the Indonesian consulate general
in Hong Kong in the future would be adjusted according to the
ongoing development in the island.
</P>
<P>
Asked on the possibility of China opening a consulate general
in Indonesia, Ghaffar said the issue is still being discussed by
the two governments.
</P>
<P>
"I am unable to give any official statement on the possibility
of China having a consulate general in Indonesia since the two
sides are still discussing the issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also could not say in which Indonesian city China would open
its consulate general.  
</P>
