<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US B-24 Bomber Remains Head for Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The crew of an American wartime
bomber were making the journey to their final resting place today
after a poignant ceremony at Beijing's Capital Airport.
</P>
<P>
The remains of the crew were handed over to the US, closing
another chapter in the history of World War Two.
</P>
<P>
The B-24 bomber disappeared without trace after a bombing raid
more than 50 years ago. The crew of ten were all killed and their
bodies, along with the wrecked aircraft had remained undisturbed
on a Chinese mountainside until recently.
</P>
<P>
Two farmers, searching for medicinal herbs in a thick forest
discovered the crashed aircraft in Xing'an County in south China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The mystery which has cast a shadow for the relatives of the
missing airmen for over half a century has now entered its final
phase with the remains of the victims homeward bound..
</P>
<P>
Mei Ping, Chinese Foreign Ministry official in charge of the
Department of Affairs of the Americas and Oceania, handed over three
black cases containing the remains of the dead airmen, and the
wrecked bomber to James Sasser, U.S ambassador to
China.
</P>
<P>
The cases were then taken by U.S army men to three grey caskets
draped with the American flag, the Stars and Stripes. The caskets
were solemnly carried to a C141 U.S cargo plane which had landed
nearby.
</P>
<P>
To the sounds of 'Taps', the gathering paid tribute to the 10
airmen who died 52 years ago in Guangxi.
</P>
<P>
At 4:30 pm on August 31, 1944, the B-24 Bomber which belonged
to US No.375 bomber squadron, a subordinate of the "Flying
Tigers," took off from an air force base in Liuzhou in Guangxi to
bomb Japanese fleets berthed at a port in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Since the home base of the bomber had been attacked by Japanese
troops, the B-24 had to divert to Guilin airport. On its way to
Guilin, the plane with its crew of young airmen aged from 19 to
26 disappeared.
</P>
<P>
Crashing on the edge of a cliff, 1,828 meters above sea level,
the bomber wreckage was scattered across a five-meter-broad and
500-meter-high crack.
</P>
<P>
The wreckage was first spotted on October 2, 1996, by two
farmers, who were looking for medicinal herbs.
</P>
<P>
The wreckage, including a piece indicating the number of the
bomber - 40783 - and remains of the US servicemen, were moved from
the site of the crash, over 90 kilometers from the Xing'an county
seat. The work took two months and 500-man hours of efforts.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin informed US President Bill
Clinton of the discovery of the wreckage in Xing'an county when
they attended an APEC meeting last November.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Defense Minister Chi Haotian, who is also vice-chairman
of the Central Military Commission and state councillor,
passed on some of the victims' belongings to US Secretary of
Defense William Perry when he visited the United States at the end
of last year.
</P>
<P>
An eight-member team headed by Alan Liotta, deputy director of
the US Defense Department POW/MIA Office, arrived on January 13 in
Xing'an county, Guangxi, to start the task of verification and
identification of the B-24 bomber.
</P>
<P>
After a two-day preliminary investigation, five 'dog' tags were
found with some remains of the victims on board.
</P>
<P>
At the handing-over ceremony, Mei Ping said, "We are gratified
that through concerted efforts of both sides, the remains of the
U.S airmen will now be repatriated to their homeland where they
may finally rest in peace."
</P>
<P>
He noted that during the Second World War, China and the United
States fought shoulder to shoulder as allies against the
Fascists. In those long and difficult days, countless heroic
people, including the American airmen, gave their lives to
the just cause of mankind.
</P>
<P>
China and the U.S have every reason now to continue to work for
peace, security and prosperity in the Asia-Pacific region and the
world as a whole, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Mei, the handing over of the wreckage remains is
one of the concrete steps China is taking to cooperate with the U.S
in finding those missing in action during the Second World War, the
Korean War, and the Viet Nam war.
</P>
<P>
"This is important not only to the American people, but also
for the Chinese to cooperate in this field, " he said.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held after the ceremony, Mr Liotta expressed
deep appreciation for China's help and cooperation in finding the
remains of U.S soldiers lost in war.
</P>
<P>
He said China and the U.S share a working relationship on this
issue. In 1994, U.S recovered the remains of American
World War Two airmen from Tibet, with the help of similiar notification
and efforts by the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
"We will also cooperate in a search to learn the fate of men
missing from both Viet Nam and Korea, " he said, adding that the
U.S is looking forward to strengthening the necessary cooperation
to fulfill our efforts on this humanitarian issue.
</P>
<P>
Over 100 U.S planes were lost during the Second World War while
flying missions into China, Mr Liotta revealed. So far only two
have been recovered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Legislature Vows to Fulfill Goals in its Term of Office (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
