<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Overseas Scientists Win Science Cooperation Awards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Four overseas scientists have
won the 1996 China International Science and Technology
Cooperation Awards established by the State Council.
</P>
<P>
The '96 award winners include American-Chinese physicist Samuel
C.C.Ting, aerodynamics expert G.S. Bisigensi from the former
Soviet Union, German biologist Uli Schwarz and American-Chinese
Architect Ieoh Ming Pei.
</P>
<P>
An official of the State Science and Technology Commission
(SSTC) said at today's news conference that China is to publicize
their major achievements both at home and abroad, in an effort to
attract more outstanding scientists to contribute to China's
science and technology development.
</P>
<P>
Sun Wanhu, deputy head of the international cooperation
department of the SSTC, said China will begin this year to promote
its science and technology cooperation with foreign consortiums
and big companies, in addition to strengthening ties with foreign
governments and research organs.
</P>
<P>
He said China is also to launch Sino-foreign cooperation in
China's research and development of the information highway, new
material, high-speed trains, electronic vehicles and other major
high-tech fields.
</P>
<P>
Sun added that some departments are drafting regulations that
will allow the establishment of Sino-foreign cooperative and
jointly run research institutions.
</P>
<P>
Samuel C.C. Ting, 61, is an internationally-known physicist and
the 1976 winner of the Nobel Prize. Thanks to his suggestion to
Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping in 1977, 10 Chinese physicists went
to Hamburg, Germany in 1978 to participate in an experiment Ting
was conducting there.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that Chinese scientists were involved
with their foreign colleagues in developed countries to carry out
important science research.
</P>
<P>
He also helped foster more than 100 Chinese physicists and post
graduate students in foreign labs that he headed.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the Institute of Electronic Engineering, led by Ting,
and the Chinese Academy of Launch Vehicle Technology participated
in the ALPHA Magnetic Spectrometer (AMS) magnet project -- the
first man-made magnet sent to space to conduct experiments.
</P>
<P>
G.S. Bisigensi, 81, was once engaged in the research of
aircraft aerodynamics and stability in the Central
Aerohydrodynamics Research Institute of the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
He has provided extensive assistance to China's design of
supersonic aircraft, and helped train China's first group of
aircraft designers.
</P>
<P>
Bisigensi also arranged for Russian experts to launch a
research program with their Chinese colleagues to design the
new-generation planes. The move is regarded as a breakthrough in
China's aviation history.
</P>
<P>
Uli Schwarz, 63, Executive Director of the Biochemistry
Laboratory of the Max Planck Gesellsehaft (MPG), helped establish
China's first open laboratory, the MPG Guest Lab in the Shanghai
Institute of Cell Biology attached to the Chinese Academy of
Sciences (CAS).
</P>
<P>
After years of work by Schwarz, the CAS and MPG established
junior scientist groups in the guest lab in hopes of attracting
outstanding young Chinese scientists from abroad to work in the
institute.
</P>
<P>
Ieoh Ming Pei, 80, world-famous American-Chinese architect, has
been invited to create some designs for the Beijing Fragrant Hill
Hotel, a Bank of China building in Hong Kong, and the headquarters
of the Bank of China in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
His work combines Chinese traditional characteristics with
modern world trends, and has contributed significantly to
advancing modern architecture in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
