<HEADLINE> 1997 Rome Marathon to Promote City's Olympic Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Rome's 1997 marathon was presented
by Mayor Francesco Rutelli on Thursday as a chance for the city to
publicise its bid to host the 2004 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Sechudled to begin at the Coliseum on the morning of March 16,
the marathon route runs through the heart of the city, past world
famous architectural landmark such as the Spanish Steps, Piazza
Navona, the Caraclla Baths and Villa Borghese.
</P>
<P>
Presenting Rome's third marathon to the press, Rutelli said
this was a crucial moment for the Italian capital's Olympic bid.
</P>
<P>
The mayor soothed fears that had been awakened last week
following comments by International Olympic Committee (IOC) member
Primo Nebiolo, saying Nebiolo was "simply saying we shouldn't take
anything for granted."
</P>
<P>
Also present, Nebiolo underlined the positive light an event
such as the city marathon could shed on Rome's chances of being
chosen as host city for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The IOC is scheduled on March 5 to meet in Lausanne to draw up
a shortlist of five cities, prior to choosing the winner in
September.
</P>
<P>
Also president of the world track and field ruling body IAAF,
Nebiolo said Rome had presented a serious Olympic project and
would certainly be able to organise "excellent" Games.
</P>
<P>
"But we have to be elected, which is why we will have to work
very hard," reminded Nebiolo.  
</P>
