<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Persistent Toxic Pollutants on Human Health to Be Listed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Persistent organic pollutants
are expected to be on a list of dangerous substances at a meeting
scheduled for next week.
</P>
<P>
"The recent scientific discoveries concerning the effects of
persistent organic pollutants (POPs) on human health are
worrying," says Lars Nordberg, deputy director of the Environment
Division of the United Nations Economic Commission for Europe
(ECE).
</P>
<P>
An ECE press release issued today said that a study by the
U.S. Academy of Sciences has shown that POPs are responsible for
more than 20,000 cases of cancer in the United States. Recent
research at the University of South Carolina Medical School proves
that industrial pollution could be responsible for falling sperm
counts.
</P>
<P>
Parties to the Convention on Long-range Transboundary Air
Pollution signed in 1979 will hold formal talks on January 20-24
within the Working Group on Strategies to decide an initial list
of POPs.
</P>
<P>
POPs, including DDT, toxaphene, chlordane, aldrin, PCBs and
dioxin, can generate cancer and damage the human reproductive
system as well as the endocrine glands and the immune system, with
a detrimental effect on physical development.
</P>
<P>
Another two sessions are scheduled for June 16-20 and autumn
respectively and negotiations on a protocol on persistent organic
pollutants are expected to conclude early 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
