<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Economy Hampered by Lack of Investment in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's economic growth has
been severely hampered due to the lack of investments in roads,
telecommunications and water supply, according to a World Bank
official.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an economic symposium here on Thursday, the bank's
Country Director for Kenya Harold Wackman said that power
shortage, poor road conditions and lack of communication
facilities had led to higher production costs, less market and
investment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The bank official noted that all sectors of the economy had
suffered from the current 10 percent electricity shortage and the
poor conditions of the country's roads, of which 34 percent were
in a "very poor condition".
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that only 75 percent of urban dwellers have
access to clean water while the percentage stands at 50 percent
in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
All these factors have significantly lowered the growth in
economic value, said Wackman, adding that in real terms, the GDP
growth rate of the east African country was only four
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Kenya needs to invest a minimum five
billion U.S. Dollars over the next five years to rehabilitate its
power, telecommunications and water infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The official said that it is necessary for a combination of
the Kenyan government, private sector and donors to provide
investments under sound policies on which the World Bank's
assistance will focus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
