<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State, Private Firms Equal on Loan-Borrowing: Top Banker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Dai Xianglong, Governor of
People's Bank of China, today called for equal treatment to be
given to both state-owned enterprises and private companies when
loans are being considered.
</P>
<P>
The emphasis for banks, he said, should be on giving high
priority to the quality of loan granting.
</P>
<P>
Dai made the call in Beijing during a meeting with leading
officials of the Agricultural Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
"I dislike such terms as 'state-owned' or 'private' while
talking about giving loans," he told the officials, "The top
concern should not be the nature of an enterprise, but the quality
of loaning."
</P>
<P>
He urged state banks to give loans in line with regulations and
the situation, but he confessed that normally there are bigger
risks for banks when granting loans to smaller firms.
</P>
<P>
"It is more safe for banks to give loans to private enterprises
that are operating well, while banks should not lend to
enterprises that are on the brink of bankruptcy, no matter whether
they are state-owned or private," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
