<HEADLINE> No Tolerance for Loss-Making Bank Officials: Top Banker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The governor of the People's
Bank of China, Dai Xianglong, said here today that state-owned
banks should not tolerate officials who are responsible for heavy
losses and that the bank heads must be punished for their
incompetence.
</P>
<P>
Dai Xianglong took the position at a meeting in Beijing with
leading officials of the Agricultural Bank of China (ABC).
</P>
<P>
The country's top banker said that state banks should focus on
the primary tasks of standardizing operations and reducing
financial risks. He stressed the importance of selecting qualified
leading officials to work in banks.
</P>
<P>
He urged state banks to investigate important cases involving
large amounts of money, and to punish officials causing the
losses, in accordance with the nature of their wrongdoings.
</P>
<P>
Chinese bankers were asked to understand the significance of
the current banking reforms and the opportunities they bring.
</P>
<P>
Dai said state banks are no longer government institutions,
rather they are enterprises in the real sense. He noted that banks
must attach greater importance to the quality of the loaning
procedures, while research should be conducted to fully understand
the market.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, some ABC officials expressed their hopes
that the government will provide a more clear definition of
state-owned commercial banks in China and create a more relaxed
environment for their development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
