<HEADLINE> India to Help Build World's Largest Accelerator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 17 (Xinhua) -- India has promised to help
the Geneva-based European Council on Nuclear Research (CERN)
construct a two-billion-U.S.-dollar hadron collider, the world's
largest accelerator, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported
today.
</P>
<P>
CERN's Research and Technical Director Dr. H. Wenninger, who is
now in the Indian city of Calcutta, was quoted as saying that the
Indian Atomic Energy Department signed a memorandum of
understanding (MOU) with the CERN, the largest accelerator complex
in the world.
</P>
<P>
He said the MOU provides for India's "effective commitment" to
the project in the form of accelerator hardware, such as
correcting magnet and other equipment, valued at 25 million U.S.
dollars in the international market.
</P>
<P>
"Detectors, which pick up all important signals of experiments,
are expected to cost a total of 1 billion U.S. dollars and India
has already been involved in a big way in building detectors,"
said Dr. Wenninger.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
