<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Faces Heavy Task of Relics Protection in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- China will have to step up its
relics protection work in 1997 -- a year full of historic,
political and economic events.
</P>
<P>
The State Cultural Relics Bureau has warned that a dam which is
scheduled to block the Yangtze River this year will force
archeologists to hastily complete work at hundreds of sites which
will be flooded by the new Three Gorge reservoir.
</P>
<P>
The bureau cautioned that state key projects may damage other
relics, and urged its workers to accelerate excavation and repair
work.
</P>
<P>
The return of Hong Kong will require cooperation between relics
departments, which will be hosting grand exhibitions in Beijing
and Hong Kong to recall the territory's past.
</P>
<P>
And relics will play a part in promoting socialist cultural and
ethical progress as part of a campaign launched by the Party last
year. Thousands of historical sites will be recognized this year
and become "Patriotism Bases" that recount stories of China's
5,000-year-old civilization and the modern revolutionary tradition.
</P>
<P>
Students can visit these sites free of charge, the bureau
announced at its annual work meeting here today.
</P>
<P>
Many archeological activities have been arranged for 1997 --
the year of ox according to the Chinese calendar -- which will be
carried out both from the air and underwater. The repair work of
some 30 major palaces, temples and caves will be completed this
year, and 100 sites will be included on a list to receive
emergency protection.
</P>
<P>
Investment in the protection of relics in China's border areas
and ethnic minority regions will be increased beginning in 1997,
the bureau decided. And a massive program will be launched to
study underground treasures in these regions.
</P>
<P>
Another complex and important task this year is to crack down
on relics thievery, including grave robbing, thefts from museums
and relics smuggling.
</P>
<P>
More than a dozen laws and regulations will be drafted and put
into effect in 1997. Additionally, cadres under age 45 are asked
to become computer literate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Legislature Vows to Fulfill Goals in its Term of Office (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature vowed
today to attain all the goals set for its current five-year term
in its remaining year in office.
</P>
<P>
Cao Zhi, secretary-general of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC), made the pledge in Beijing while
addressing a reception attended by deputies to the NPC,
celebrating the upcoming traditional Spring Festival.
</P>
<P>
"This year will be crucial for the Eighth NPC and its Standing
Committee. They will have to reach all the goals mapped out for
the five-year term of office, since we still have much complicated
and heavy work to to in the remaining year," he told the NPC
deputies.
</P>
<P>
The top legislature examined 31 laws and decisions on Chinese
law in 1996, approving 22 measures during the year.
</P>
<P>
"Our legislation pace was markedly quickened, and our
legislation plan to pass enough laws to basically facilitate the
establishment of a market economy in the country is expected to
be realized," Cao claimed.
</P>
<P>
According to its legislation program of more than 100 laws and
decisions, the lawmakers still have around 30 laws and decisions
that need to be formulated, examined and adopted before March of
1998 when the current NPC ends.
</P>
<P>
The 30 laws to be formulated will be more complicated and
difficult, because they involve issues with no experiences to
draw on, or are still under dispute. They include new laws on
supervision, securities and contracts.
</P>
<P>
Cao promised that the NPC and its Standing Committee will work
harder to ensure that all laws made are of high quality.
</P>
<P>
Law enforcement has been the Achilles' heel of China. To make
up for the shortcomings, the top legislature has started to beef
up the efforts of supervision according to the Chinese
constitution.
</P>
<P>
The NPC Standing Committee organized 21 inspection tours last
year to 21 provinces, cities and autonomous regions to see how the
environmental, educational, labor, agricultural laws and the law
on public order were being observed and implemented.
</P>
<P>
Eight vice-chairmen of the NPC Standing Committee participated
in the inspection tours, which is unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
Similar supervisory efforts will be further reinforced this
year, especially the checking of the work of the State Council and
relative departments, the Supreme People's Court and the Supreme
People's Procuratorate, Cao said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
