<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Prime Minister Calls for National Harmony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Deve Gowda
today called on the Indian people to work for national harmony and
fight against divisive and disruptive forces in the country.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a function after giving the 1994 harmony award here,
the prime minister said that India's pluralistic society was
undergoing social transition, which has given rise at times to
certain frictions in the name of religion, region or caste.
</P>
<P>
He said that the people professing different faiths, speaking
different languages and belonging to different castes have been
living in the country in harmony for thousands of years and it was
only in the later part of this century that such differences were
exploited to create rifts between the people. He warned that such
frictions should not be allowed to be capitalized by divisive
forces in the country.
</P>
<P>
He exhorted non-governmental organizations to supplement
efforts of the government to maintain communal harmony.  
</P>
</TEXT>
