<HEADLINE> &AMP;0             New Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The demands of the Philippine
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) will be discussed at peace
talks when they are resumed on February 25, the Philippine News
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a local report said that the MILF wanted "total
independence" for 12 provinces in Mindanao in southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Fortunato Abat, chairman of the Philippine government panel of
the peace talks, was quoted as saying that the MILF has not yet
submitted formally its demands to the government panel, so he
could not comment on the reported MILF demand for "total
independence."
</P>
<P>
MILF Vice Chairman Nur Jaafar said that the Muslim group wanted
independence for North and South Cotabato, Zamboanga del Sur,
Zamboanga del Norte, Lanao del Sur, Lanao del Norte, Maguindanao,
Sultan Kudarat, Sulu, Tawi-Tawi, Basilan and Sarangani.
</P>
<P>
However, Jaafar did not specify what form of "total
independence" the MILF wants and said that "there are many forms
of independence," the report said.  
</P>
