<HEADLINE> Ramos Orders Continuing Drive Against Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Ramos today
ordered a continuing drive against corruption and directed heads
of government departments to monitor the status of cases of those
charged in court.
</P>
<P>
In a directive to all heads of departments and agencies,
including government-owned corporations, Ramos told them to submit
a monthly report on the preventive, prosecutory and rehabilitative
measures they are implementing to fight graft and corruption.
</P>
<P>
"A regular assessment of these measures and their impact on our
anti-graft and corruption campaign will be continuously undertaken
by the Office of the President," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president reminded them that the anti-graft campaign is
part of his administration's program of making public services
more effective and efficient.
</P>
<P>
Ramos ordered Press Secretary Hector Villanueva to issue a list
of cases involving VIP's or "big fish" which have already been
acted upon.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he ordered Executive Secretary Ruben Torres
to refine a proposed bill now pending in Congress to make it more
applicable to Philippine conditions and give stiffer penalties for
the perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Presidential Management Staff Secretary Alexander
Aguirre today convened a conference on anti-graft and corruption
to tell all heads of departments to pursue without letup the drive
against graft and corruption in the government.
</P>
<P>
Billions of pesos are lost annually by the government in terms
of revenues due to graft and corruption, it was reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
