<HEADLINE> Manila to Help Iraq's Bid for Lifting Trade Embargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines will help Iraq
in securing the support of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) for an early lifting of the UN trade embargo on
Iraq, President Fidel Ramos said today.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government is ready to discuss Iraq's request
with ASEAN's six other members, Ramos told visiting Chairman of
the Iraqi National Assembly Saadoun Hamadi during a 30-minute
meeting at the Presidential Palace here.
</P>
<P>
"The Philippines, as a member of ASEAN and as a sovereign
country, would like to be of utmost assistance to Iraq. But,
perhaps, an ASEAN team effort would be more effective," said
Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Hamadi said that he believes the Philippines, being a prominent
member of ASEAN, can play a role in convincing the UN Security
Council to lift the sanction.
</P>
<P>
He told Ramos that Iraq is willing and prepared to implement
the agreements reached with the UN to enable itself to participate
in global trade.
</P>
<P>
Hamadi conveyed Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's appreciation
for the participation of the Philippines in the UN-initiated
oil-for-food countertrade arrangement allowing Iraq to export oil
in exchange for food and medical supplies.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine International Trading Corporation will undertake
the export of food products, medicines, and pharmaceuticals to
Iraq while targeting 20 to 30 percent of the 2 billion US dollars
worth of oil that Iraq is allowed to export every six months.
</P>
<P>
Hamadi said that Iraq wants to establish a long-term
relationship with the Philippines based on "mutual benefit,
complementarity of interests and mutual trust."
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi official and his delegation arrived here on Thursday
after visiting Malaysia and Indonesia, where Hamadi brought up the
same subject of drawing ASEAN's support for lifting the UN
embargo.  
</P>
</TEXT>
