<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Regards EC's Anti-dumping Duty as Conspiracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 17 (Xinhua) -- A Pakistan official said
today that the imposition of provisional anti-dumping duties by
the European Community (EC) against textile imports was a
conspiracy against the country's economic interests.
</P>
<P>
Akber Sheikh, convenor of a special committee on the World
Trade Organization (WTO) of All Pakistan Textile Mills
Association, made the remarks in Lahore, the capital of Punjab
province, according to a APP report today.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh said that the EC's decision is a political step of
importing countries to protect their local textile and allied
industry.
</P>
<P>
Under the WTO, the importing countries have to remove the quota
restrictions by 2005.
</P>
<P>
These countries want to provide special protection to their
local industries so that they could achieve maximum economic
strength and viability by the time when these restrictions will be
lifted, he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that such an attitude is negative and a
conspiracy against the developing countries, especially for the
countries like Pakistan which mainly depend on its cotton and
textile exports for their foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of Pakistan's exports are textile related.
</P>
<P>
He was of the view that the recently imposed provisional duties
on Pakistani cotton grey cloth by the EC is biased as 30 percent
duty has been imposed on Pakistani exporters whereas other
countries have been assessed at about 15 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
