<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Hospitals to Adopt Blue Cross As Symbol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- China's hospitals, clinics and
other medical institutes will adopt a blue cross as a symbol of
identification beginning in May, according to a decision made by
the Ministry of Public Health (MPH).
</P>
<P>
The ministry introduced the new sign in an attempt to stop the
illegal use of the internationally-recognized Red Cross logo,
which has been used by some medical institutes which are not
members of the Red Cross Society, said Yi Mei, a MPH official
responsible for management in the health sector.
</P>
<P>
"We have to unify the use of the hospitals' symbol in order to
ensure no infringements are made upon the Red Cross sign," Yi told
Xinhua News Agency on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The blue-and-white sign will be placed at either the entrance
or on top of hospital buildings, and should be easily visible from
many directions and from a certain distance, according to the
decision.
</P>
<P>
The blue cross should be able to be seen at the entrance of
emergency wards at night. Medical workers must wear lab coats and
name tags bearing the sign, and it will also be painted on
ambulances.
</P>
<P>
"The unified use of the sign is designed to make it more
convenient for people to locate medical care facilities," Yi said.
</P>
<P>
Currently in China, many people mistakenly think the red cross
indicates a hospital due to wrong use of the sign, she noted.
</P>
<P>
The Law on the Red Cross Society and the Methods Concerning the
Use of the Red Cross Sign have forbidden non-society members from
adopting the sign in China.
</P>
<P>
"However, many of them ignore the laws and use the red cross
everywhere. That confuses people," Yi said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
