<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- After one black week of atmospheric pollution, French
Environment Minister Corinne Lepage Thursday called for the
immediate application of a law on air pollution adopted 15 days
ago, which aims to restrict automobile circulations. The central
city of Lyon Thursday banned heavy trucks from its using its roads
for transitional purpose.
</P>
<P>
-- In Israel, 185,000 members of the Kibbutz communities who
strictly live up to the principles of socialism are making use of
multimedia networks to strengthen their organization, and to fend
off the wave of liberalism and individualism.
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Benyamin Netanyahu Thursday justified
the agreement on Hebron he signed with PLO leader Yasser Arafat
before the Knesset (parliament), which adopted the text in the
evening.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- For the first time in France, measures to ban circulation of
heavy trucks were taken Thursday in Lyon to lower the level of
atmospheric pollution caused by automobiles, which stays alarmingly
high in several major French cities.
</P>
<P>
-- The French economy enjoyed a slight growth in the third
quarter of 1996 due to an increase of consumption by French
households, especially in buying automobiles, said the official
statistics bureau INSEE.  
</P>
