<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai, Canadian Prime Ministers Hold Talks in Bangkok </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh held talks with his Canadian counterpart Jean
Chretien here today at the Government House focusing on upgrading
bilateral investment and trade relations.
</P>
<P>
Jean Chretien arrived here on Thursday evening on a five-day
official visit to Thailand with a 450-strong entourage, comprising
provincial and territorial governors and 300 business people.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the two prime ministers also discussed
trade and investment liberalization under the Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum. Canada is to host this year's
APEC leaders' informal meeting in November.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, the two prime ministers witnessed the signing
of 10 bilateral agreements or memorandums of understanding (MOU)
on cooperation in investment promotion and protection, finance,
education, environment, academics, manufacturing and exports.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is Canada's 20th largest export market and its second
largest export market in ASEAN, while Canada is Thailand's 12th
largest export market.
</P>
<P>
With a joint goal of increasing two-way trade to 2 billion US
dollars by 1999, the figure has been growing at nearly 13 percent
annually and last year exceeded 1.2 billion dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
