<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Africa's New Extradition Act Takes Effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Extradition Amendment
Act, aimed at streamlining extradition procedures in South
Africa, came into effect today, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela earlier accepted a
recommendation from Justice Minister Dullah Omar in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The new act is another
important step towards curtailing money laundering, drug trafficking
and corruption, Omar said in an earlier statement.
</P>
<P>
"It will enable South Africa to play a meaningful role in the fight
against these social evils," he added.
</P>
<P>
The new law provides for the designation of states to which
extradition may be affected in the absence of formal agreement,
making the surrender of individuals to other countries possible
without the consent of the president.
</P>
<P>
It also provides for the issuing of warrants of arrest of suspects
and their further detention.
</P>
<P>
The act further regulates the procedures for an appeal by an
individual against whom an order for extradition has been issued.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
