<HEADLINE> S. African Students Get 6 Million U.S. Dollar UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Development
Program (UNDP) has allocated six million US Dollars to support South
African students and lecturers at formerly black tertiary
institutions this year, said local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in Pretoria on Thursday, the UNDP said
the Educational and Training Program for Southern Africa
(UNETPSA) and the South African government signed two project
agreements to this effect last month.
</P>
<P>
UNETPSA program co-ordinator Angela Masithela said that more than
3,000 people will benefit from the UN grant, part of it already
available to related institutions.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the money will be used for student scholarships and
for human resource development activities like training lecturers,
administrators and managers, added Masithela. 
</P>
