<HEADLINE> Saddam: Iraq Not Defeated in Gulf War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
said here today Iraq was not defeated in the Gulf war, the
official Iraqi news agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
In a televised address today marking the 6th anniversary of the
start of the Gulf War in 1991, the president said Iraq's enemies
destroyed the weapons and supplies of the Iraqi army and the
country's national industry, but the Iraqis were not defeated,
according to the INA.
</P>
<P>
Apparently commenting on the current United Nations sanctions
against Iraq, Saddam claimed that the U.S.-led allies failed to
achieve their basic strategic objectives despite the joint
military actions six years ago, so they had to resort to prolonged
embargoes to kill more Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has maintained sanctions against Iraq since the Iraqi
invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, the Iraqi president also urged the people of
other Arab states not to follow some of their rulers who set "the
bad examples" for them. He did not elaborate, however.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, Saddam strongly criticized some of the other
Arab leaders for bowing to the will of the West and following the
U.S. orders to harm Iraq. But he did not specify by name. 
</P>
</TEXT>
