<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong, Singapore Sign Pact on Regulating Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong and Singapore, two
financial hubs in Asia, have vowed to work closely in regulating
their financial markets, according to reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum of understanding was signed in Singapore on
Thursday by Hong Kong's Securities and Futures Commission (SFC)
and the Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS).
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the SFC said the agreement would
facilitate exchange of information between the two financial
watchdogs on the regulation of securities, futures and options
trading.
</P>
<P>
SFC Chairman Anthony Neoh said the agreement aimed "to
strengthen the enforcement of laws and regulations for the
protection of investors and the prevention of securities and
futures fraud and market malpractice."
</P>
<P>
The agreement "is in recognition of the increasing
international activity in the securities, futures and options
markets in both jurisdictions and the need for regulatory
cooperation between the two regulatory bodies," the MAS said.
</P>
<P>
The pact, according to the MAS, provided a framework for
cooperation, increased mutual understanding and the exchange of
information "on a best effort basis" and to the extent permitted
by the laws of Hong Kong and Singapore.  
</P>
</TEXT>
