<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Issues Regulation on Labor Flow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 17 (Xinhua) -- People who want to change jobs
in China are not allowed to reveal state secrets or leave key
projects they are involved in, according to a regulation recently
adopted by Shanghai's municipal legislature, which is intended to
impart some order to the movement of labor in the city.
</P>
<P>
The regulation also says that those who want to leave their
work units cannot infringe on employers' intellectual property
rights or reveal business secrets.
</P>
<P>
Those who are in charge of key engineering or research projects
cannot move to other locations without permission of their work
units, before the projects' completion.
</P>
<P>
With China's reforms and opening-up, greater numbers of people
have taken to changing their work, but some leave without a word,
making off with valuable data and causing considerable problems
for their employers.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulation, employees must notify the employer
a certain amount of time in advance if they want to resign or
break a contract with a work unit, and in some cases must pay a
certain amount of compensation to the employer.
</P>
<P>
When a work unit receives a written application for
resignation, it also must make a decision within a certain period
of time.
</P>
<P>
Businesses are not allowed to offer services of the flow of
talents without permission of the municipal labor department,
according to the regulation, and disputes can be submitted to
labor departments or courts for arbitration.
</P>
<P>
The regulation will take effect on April 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Security Panel Setup Unseals Pandora's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The formation of the Council
for Defense and National Security (CDNS) has sparked a series of
controversies in Pakistan's political arena.
</P>
<P>
CDNS, formed just a little more than a week ago and termed as
"a purely advisory body" by President Farooq Leghari, has become
one of the major focuses in Pakistan especially within the context
of the current political imbroglio.
</P>
<P>
The 10-member council was set up on January 6, less than a
month before the February 3 general elections, with its envisaged
role to aid and advise the government on key national issues
including declaration of emergency.
</P>
<P>
The new advisory body, headed by President Leghari, who is also
supreme commander of the armed forces, comprises the prime
minister, chairman of the joint chiefs of staff committee, the
army, the navy and the air force chiefs and ministers of defense,
foreign affairs and interior.
</P>
<P>
In the highly-charged political situation in the country and
against the background of a general hostile response to its very
creation, CDNS had its first meeting the following day of its
setup with a special reference to the holding of forthcoming
polls.
</P>
<P>
However, the formation of the council has generated heated
arguments and counter-arguments with certain sections defending
and others vehemently opposing it.
</P>
<P>
The major thrust of the objections against CDNS is that the
creation, in effect, would clip the wings of democracy by
involving the armed forces in political decision making.
</P>
<P>
The formation of the council by the two-month-old caretaker
government came no less than a "surprising move" to the general
public.
</P>
<P>
It has certainly created a strong suspicion despite the claims
that the council has only recommendatory status to advise the
government, and "it would not be supra-constitutional,
supra-parliamentary or supra-governmental body."
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that an intriguing function of CDNS would
be the "definition of the task of armed forces of Pakistan in
accordance with the national strategy."
</P>
<P>
CDNS will have no limits or parameters for its "advisory"
functions. It can make recommendations covering "practically
everything relating to internal security, proclamations of
emergency and any other matter of national importance referred to
the Council... by the President or Prime Minister."
</P>
<P>
President Leghari has said that the formation of the council is
not a prelude to martial law or presidential system. And General
Jehangir Karamat, Chief of Army Staff, has said that as far as the
Army is concerned CDNS is an "interim arrangement" and not a
permanent body.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, since the lifting of Martial Law in 1985, this
will be the first time that the armed forces will formally
participate in political proceedings of the country.
</P>
<P>
Even though the council is said to be an advisory body, it is
widely believed here that it will have all the political clout and
would be in a position to dictate its recommendations to the
political leadership.
</P>
<P>
Some critics of the plan say that the formation of CDNS will
dilute parliamentary system and aggravate tensions between the
Army and the government owing to restrictions on the latter's
role.
</P>
<P>
They said that in its 50 years of existence, Pakistan has been
ruled directly by the armed forces for 25 years. The military has
remained a very powerful factor in the political affairs of the
country even after the death of General Zia-ul-Haq.
</P>
<P>
The direct involvement of the Army through three martial laws
did not help resolve the country's problems. On the contrary, its
direct and indirect interventions further added to the problems.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, those who favor it have argued that the council will
lead to much better coordination and reduce tensions between the
so-called "troika" -- the Army, the President and the Prime
Minister.
</P>
<P>
They said the involvement of the Army in economic issues of the
country cannot be criticized because it is linked with defending
the nation's borders. A country's security today is not just its
borders but also the economic health of the country, they argued.
</P>
<P>
CDNS, as said in an article carried by the major English daily
"The News", is to "restrain the unbridled financial and political
ambitions of our elected representatives and their friends and
relations which were proving detrimental to the security of the
nation and the well being of the poor masses."
</P>
<P>
And observers here believe that it will also help ensure the
continuity of the next government in office for the full length of
its term, something that had become impossible in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, with the formation of CDNS, the members will, at
least, sit face to face arguing their differences and discussing
the best possible way to act in the national interest.
</P>
<P>
It is most possible that the general elections are to be held
on February 3 as repeatedly assured by the government, now the
question remains as what is the haste in creating such a council
merely less than a month before the polls?
</P>
<P>
CDNS, in any case, has sparked a lot of controversies in this
country which is facing enormous economic problems, and it will be
quite some time before a consensus can be found.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
