<HEADLINE> Ethnic Monority Radio, TV Programs Prosperous in Xinjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, January 17 (Xinhua) -- A large number of radio and TV
stations in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region are
broadcasting their programs in at least two languages, according
to the regional government.
</P>
<P>
An audio and visual transmitting network in ethnic languages,
with China Central Television (CCTV) and the regional radio and TV
stations as the main body, has gone into use.
</P>
<P>
The Xinjiang Regional People's Radio Station is the first of
its kind in China to broadcast in four ethnic minority languages
in addition to the standard Chinese, and the regional TV station
is the first in the country to broadcast in three languages via
satellite.
</P>
<P>
Some autonomous prefectures also have their programs
broadcasted in local languages, said Dong Sen, deputy-secretary
general of the Ethnic Minority Radio and TV Society.
</P>
<P>
The regional radio, TV and film department has set up a TV
program translation center to provide TV programs in local
languages. Some prefectures have found their own translation
departments, Dong noted.
</P>
<P>
Last year, some 1,000 TV programs were broadcast in ethnic
minority languages, winning widespread support from the public.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a number of local reporters and editors have become
the backbone of regional radio and TV circles. Ethnic minority
people account for over two thirds of the total staff at the
Xinjiang Regional People's Radio Station.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, ethnic minority reporters and editors have become
more competent over recent years. One ethnic minority reporter won
a state-level journalist prize in 1994, and another ethnic mority
editors won another journalist prize the following year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
