<HEADLINE> Economic Panel Held Meeting in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The 8th session of the Economic
Panel of the Preparatory Committee of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) concluded today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting, members listened to briefings given
by officials from the British Hong Kong government as well as
leading members of the Kowloon-Guangzhou Railway Corporation and the
Mass Transit Railway Corporation, which dealt with the lastest
project of the Western Corridor Railway and the plan to build a
subway branch line at Tseung Kwan O. The group also held
discussions on these matters.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the British Hong Kong government issued a project to
revise the building plan for the Western Corridor Railway, and
made numerous adjustments on the previous plan.
</P>
<P>
The officials of the British Hong Kong government and the
leading members of the Kowloon-Guangzhou Railway Corporation gave
detailed explanations of the changes, and those from the Mass
Transit Railway Corporation agreed with the need to build the
subway branch line.
</P>
<P>
They said further study will be conducted on the two projects,
and final decisions will be made next year.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Economic Panel said they have always maintained
a positive attitude on the construction of Hong Kong's
infrastructure, because it will play an important role in
improving Hong Kong's traffic and economic development.
</P>
<P>
The study of the two projects should be actively carried
out. But as construction will not begin until July 1, 1997, the
future SAR government should make the final decisions on the
plans, they said.
</P>
<P>
They noted the British side should continue to negotiate with
the Chinese side on major issues concerning the two projects, via
the Sino-British Joint Liaison Group and before the establishment
of the SAR government.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side will listen to and respect the opinions of the
Chief Executive during the negotiation, they added.
</P>
<P>
Members also discussed issues of the development of Hong Kong's
manufacturing industry and how Hong Kong will participate in the
exploration of the central and western areas, and suggested
turning over the relevant opinions to the SAR government for
reference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
