<HEADLINE> Health Care for People in Guangxi Greatly Improving: Statistics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The average life expectancy of
the residents in southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region has been raised to 71.4 years as a result of improved
healthcare services and living standards.
</P>
<P>
The figure, compared with the record of 47 years before the
founding of New China in 1949, is now 1.4 years higher than the
state's average level, according to statistics released by the
Regional Department of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
The department is preparing for a regional conference next week
to outline local healthcare work for the next four years.
</P>
<P>
By 1995, Guangxi had established more than 1,700 hospitals with
about 80,000 beds and nearly 120,000 medics, which means that two
beds and three medical workers are available for every 1,000
people.
</P>
<P>
China's health departments often use such statistics to
partially measure the level of medical care work.
</P>
<P>
The incidence rate of infectious diseases has dropped by 93.8
percent since the 1950s, from 2,459 people per 100,000, to 153
people per 100,000 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the death rate of patients suffering from infectious
diseases has fallen from 135 per million to 4.7 per million.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi leads the country in successfully eliminating smallpox,
snail fever and filariasis in the past decades, as well as
leprosy, polio and malaria.
</P>
<P>
The region has set up 103 institutes in charge of maternal and
infant health care and 149 baby-friendly hospitals, where
breast-feeding is encouraged.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
