<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Winter Water Conservation Efforts In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- China has marked 21.5 billion
yuan for repairs on water control projects that were damaged by
flooding and other natural disasters last year.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 60 percent of the repairs have been completed, according
to reports from construction sites in various provinces.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 5.3 billion work days have been spent on
water control projects, and more than seven billion cubic meters
of earth have been moved. The number of laborers at construction
sites across China was as high as 111 million a day.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-three of the 30 provinces and autonomous regions on the
Chinese mainland have set up special funds for building and
repairing water conservation areas.
</P>
<P>
Leading grain producing areas like Henan, Anhui, and Sichuan
provinces have mobilized 10 million people a day to work on water
facilities. About a third of the rural workforce in Hebei, Shanxi,
Hubei, Hunan, and Hainan provinces are busy repairing damaged
projects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
