<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Trade Deficit Up in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' trade deficit
in the first 11 month of last year swelled to 10.95 billion U.S.
dollars from 8.14 billion dollars posted in the same period of
1995, up by 34.5 percent, the National Statistics Office said
today.
</P>
<P>
In a report released here, the office said that payments for
imported goods grew by 23.5 percent to 29.61 billion dollars
during the period while receipts from exports improved by 17.9
percent to 18.66 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The balance of trade in goods was in deficit and went up by
34.5 percent to 10.95 billion dollars from 8.14 billion dollars in
1995," the office said.
</P>
<P>
The office said that trade transactions between the Philippines
and the rest of the world during the 11 months amounted to 48.27
billion dollars, up by 21.3 percent from 39.79 billion dollars in
1995.
</P>
<P>
The office attributed the country's higher trade deficit in the
year to the increase in imports of electronics and components,
which went up by 29 percent over the previous year, and a 48
percent increase in the payments for mineral fuels, lubricants and
related materials.
</P>
<P>
Japan, the United States, South Korea and Singapore are the
major trade partners of the Philippines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
