<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Chinese Port to Add 14 Deepwater Berths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Xiamen, in east China's Fujian
Province, expects to add 14 deepwater berths to help handle the
anticipated increase in trade in the special economic zone during
the Ninth Five-Year Plan.
</P>
<P>
Also to be built are five mid-sized berths and three wharves
for special use, sources say.
</P>
<P>
The projects will cost about 4.6 billion yuan, and are expected
to bring an added handling capacity of 19 million tons to Xiamen
Port, according to local port authorities.
</P>
<P>
The deepwater berths will mainly be located at Dongdu, Xiangyu,
Haicang, and Paitou, and the mid-sized ones at such places as
Liuwudian, Gaoqi, and Xinglin. The special-use wharves include a
35,000-tonnage-ship power plant wharf, a 100,000-tonnage oil and
chemicals wharf, and a 3,000-tonnage oil and gas wharf. 
</P>
</TEXT>
