<HEADLINE> Kuwait Wants to Bolster Ties with US: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait is keen on
bolstering ties of friendship and cooperation with the United
States in various spheres, Kuwaiti Crown Prince and Prime
Minister Sheikh Saad Al-Abdallah Al-Sabah said Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks while with a U.S. senators delegation
headed by Ted Stevens, Chairman of the U.S. Congress's National
Fund Committee, and commander of the U.S. Central Command General
Benford B. who also arrived in Kuwait leading a military
delegation.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the two sides covered topics on further
bolstering the already-strong bilateral relations. Regional issues
of mutual concern were also discussed, a statement issued by the
Crown Prince's office said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. senators' delegation and the military delegation
arrived here Thursday for a three-day official visit, the first
time for U.S. official delegations came to visit Kuwait since the
beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., a main ally of Kuwait, led a multi-national coalition
force in 1991 to drive Iraqi troops out of Kuwait in the Gulf
War. The two countries signed a military defense cooperation
agreement following the Gulf War, under which the U.S. is
committed to maintaining security and stability of the small
oil-rich Gulf country besides selling a large amount of arms to it
and conducting frequent military maneuvers with its troops.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait and the U.S. have also maintained close ties and
cooperation in other fields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
