<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 07:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Completes Hebron Redeployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Early this morning, Israeli
army completed its long-awaited redeployment in the West Bank
town of Hebron, less than eight hours after the Knesset (Israel's
parliament) approved the pullback agreement.
</P>
<P>
At around 6:15 a.m. local time (0415 GMT) this morning, the
Israeli army command in Hebron handed over the military
building in the city to his Palestinian counterpart, a formal
action completing the redeployment.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army later announced the conclusion of the
redeployment in a statement issued shortly before 7:00 a.m. local
time (0500 GMT), with a Palestinian flag that had been hung and
flying over the military building.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of cheering local Palestinians, gathered around the
military building throughout the night, were pouring into the
courtyard of the building to celebrate the ending of 30-year
Israeli rule of the city.
</P>
<P>
Jibril Rajoub, head of the Palestinian Preventive Security
forces in the West Bank, said that he had been in the building
for five times as an Israeli prisoner, and now he came to take
control.
</P>
<P>
Rajoub, a Hebron native, said that the Palestinians would
try to fulfill their commitments reached in the Hebron accord,
and he hoped that the Israelis would do the same.
</P>
<P>
With Palestinian policemen taking over observation positions
close to the Jewish neighborhood, the residents in Hebron, Jews
and Palestinians alike, have started a new era, in which they
will live side-by-side, hopefully in a peaceful way.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday night, the Knesset ratified the Hebron accord,
in an 87 to 17 vote with one abstention, giving the
green light to the Israeli army to redeploy its troops in the
West Bank town.
</P>
<P>
The accord was initialed Wednesday morning at the end of a
summit meeting between Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu
and Palestinian Authority (PA) President Yasser Arafat, held at
the Erez checkpoint between Israel and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
In the early hours of Thursday morning, the Israeli cabinet,
after nearly 12 hours of deliberation, approved the
agreement by an 11 to 7 vote, followed immediately by the
dramatic resignation of diehard opponent Science Minister Ze'ev
Begin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
