<HEADLINE> Asian Weightlifting Championships to Held in Yangzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGZHOU, China, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The 29th men's and 10th
women's Asian Weightlifting Championships, the largest of the kind
ever in the continent, will be held in Yangzhou, China from July 5
through 15.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here on Friday, the organizing committee
of the AWC said the championships will feature 10 categories for
men and nine for women. A total of 240 weightlifters are expected
to enter the competition.
</P>
<P>
The championships, which had been decided to be staged in
Thailand after an Asian Weightlifting Congress meeting in 1995,
had to be shifted to China's Yangzhou because this year's World
Weightlifting Championships will be hosted by Thailand.
</P>
<P>
According to the organizing committee, women's weightlifting
has been concluded officially in the program of the Sydney
Olympics in 2000.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that five gold medals will be added in the
competition.
</P>
<P>
China is the strongest nation in the women's weightlifting,
holding 26 world records.
</P>
<P>
China won two gold medals at the Atlanta Olympic Games in the
men's weightlifting.
</P>
<P>
At the last Asian Weightlifting Championships in Japan in 1995,
China finished first overall both in the men's and women's
competitions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
