<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPP, Funcinpec Leadership Meet for Boosting Consultations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The compromising committee
of Cambodia's coalition parties met on Thursday night to discuss
ways to boost consultations and avoid rifts ahead in the
forthcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
About 20 senior officials from the ruling parties, the
Funcinpec Party and the Cambodian People's Party (CPP) attended
the three-hour dinner meeting presided over by Co-Deputy Prime
Ministers Sar Kheng and Ing Kiet.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, the first this year, followed a previous session
one month ago which helped to a bridge political rift between
coalition partners when tension was growing.
</P>
<P>
Sar Kheng told reporters after the meeting that decisions on
some measures to boost cooperation between the two parties were
made, and better mutual understanding have been achieved at the
meeting which was to benefit the country's stability and
development.
</P>
<P>
Both sides promised to make more efforts to ensure stability of
the nation and to ease tension between the two parties, and agreed
that any troop movement ordered by a party should be halted and
the Royal Cambodian Armed Forces should act under the command of
the headquarters of the joint general staff, Sar Kheng said.
</P>
<P>
He affirmed that the participants also voiced their backing for
the local and national elections set respectively for 1997 and
1998.
</P>
<P>
Sar Kheng also said that participants reviewed the
implementation of the accord of alliance between the two parties
and agreed with the assessment that much had bee achieved in
carrying out the accord, although a number of problems had to be
addressed.
</P>
<P>
They also upheld the system of co-prime ministers making
regular reports to the King every two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed to create an ad hoc-group to completely review
the accord, and make amendments and additions to it in light of
current situations.
</P>
<P>
According to Sar Kheng, the ad-hoc group would submit a joint
report to the top leaders of the two parties after finishing their
assignments.
</P>
<P>
In order for the timely exchange of information and to tackle
rifts arising, Sar Kheng said a decision was reached at the
meeting to set up a permanent office of the compromising
committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
