<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Soccer Calls for Clean Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Football
Confederation warned on Friday that players and officials will be
punished severely should they are caught of stimulating corruption
and violence.
</P>
<P>
"Asian football is on the move. We cannot afford to let
corruption in the guise of match-fixing or basically corrupt
players and officials impede this march towards progress," said
AFC secretary Peter Velappan in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The warning was issued at the time when a Malaysian businessman
and three English soccer players are on trial in England on
charges of match fixing.
</P>
<P>
Former Liverpool and Southampton goalkeeper Bruce Grobbelaar
and former Wimbledon goalkeeper Hans Segers are accused of playing
fake games for money from gambling syndicates in Indonesia and
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Heng Suan Lim acted as the British contact for the
syndicates and former Wimbledon striker John Fashanu handed over
the money. All the defendants have pleaded innocent.
</P>
<P>
Velappan warned that his warning "should be taken seriously by
all those involved in football in Asia, and we will not be lenient
towards anyone found guilty of corrupt activities in Asian
football." 
</P>
</TEXT>
