<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hun Sen Rules Out Deal With Laotian Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Second Prime Minister Hun
Sen has ruled out a deal to allow the Laotian rebels to take
refuge in Cambodia in exchange for their promise to help undermine
the Khmer Rouge, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a school inauguration ceremony in Preah Vihear
province Thursday, Hun Sen said that "the Laotians who once
cooperated with the Khmer Rouge" promised to "help us fight the
Khmer Rouge and destroy their weapon warehouses," if "we agree to
provide them with an asylum at the border of the provinces of
Preah Vihear and Stung Treng."
</P>
<P>
The Laotians also promised to give 500,000 U.S. dollars in
medical supplies in exchange for areas to train their troops armed
with tanks, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We can not accept the deal because it violates the sovereignty
of Laos," Hun Sen said.
</P>
<P>
Describing the idea as "scandalous," he said the rebel group
might seek a Cambodian ally who would "use these Laotians, and the
Khmer Rouge, as a weapon."
</P>
<P>
He also accused some Cambodian generals and colonels of keeping
company of the Laotian rebels and giving them Cambodian military
uniforms and even taking them to vacations on the coast.
</P>
<P>
Warning them to stop the acts that "jeopardize our friendship
with Laos," he said "I made the revelations because I am afraid
someone else might agree to the deal although I have rejected it."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
