<HEADLINE> Additional Funds for Security in Japanese Overseas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government has
approved today an additional spending to tighten security at its
diplomatic establishments abroad, the Kyodo news service reported.
</P>
<P>
Japan will spend 2.074 billion yen (18.85 million U.S. dollars)
to equip its embassies in high-risk nations with X-ray bomb
detectors, metal sensors, stronger fences, mobile phones and
digital cellular phones, the news service said.
</P>
<P>
The additional funds came at a time when security arrangements
for Japan's overseas establishments had been called into question
following the December 17 takeover of the Japanese ambassador's
residence in Lima by the Peruvian rebels.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, who are still holding 74 hostages, have already
occupied the ambassador's residence for a month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
