<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 9th Five-Year Plan Approved by NDC in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The National Development
Council (NDC) of India has approved the approach document
envisaging 7 percent accelerated growth in the Ninth Five-Year
Plan (1998-2002).
</P>
<P>
A resolution to this effect was passed unanimously at the end
of the council's day-long meeting here on Thursday with a call
from Prime Minister Deve Gowda for collective efforts by the
center and states to raise resources to the tune of 8,750 billion
rupees (246.5 billion US dollars) for implementing the plan.
</P>
<P>
The NDC meeting also approved the investment rate of 28.6
percent, the savings rate of 26.2 percent and the expected
incremental capital output ratio of 4.08.
</P>
<P>
Virtually every chief minister favored a seven percent growth
rate for the ninth Five-Year plan, rejecting suggestions that a
lower growth rate may be more realistic.
</P>
<P>
They said that this was needed to meet the paramount objectives
of expanding productive employment, removing poverty and
generating adequate public resources to meet the basic social
needs of the growing population.
</P>
<P>
The leaders said that seven percent growth rate will not happen
by itself. It requires higher rates of investment, higher savings
rate from both domestic and foreign sources and greater efficiency
and productivity from the investments made.
</P>
<P>
Endorsing the approach document, chief ministers of various
states and heads of union territories, however, demanded
decentralization of powers of the central government and
revolution of financial resources.
</P>
<P>
The National Development Council is composed of the chief
ministers of various states and heads of union territories with
the prime minister as its chairman.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
