<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Criticizes Human Rights Watch for Report (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The leader of the China Society
for the Study of Human Rights said in an interview with Xinhua
today that the Chapter on China of the "World Report 1997"
released by Human Rights Watch on December 4 last year contains
malicious and slanderous attacks against China's human rights
situation and is frivolous and unjust.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the report makes groundless accusations
and intentionally fabricates 10 to 20 so-called individual cases
in order to frame up charges on criminal violations of human
rights against China and vilify the country.
</P>
<P>
For example, he noted, the report describes Guo Haifeng, a
convicted rapist, as a "political prisoner", and says that Guo's
1996 imprisonment was the result of his "helping a third dissident
leader escape to the United States".
</P>
<P>
According to the investigation report, on January 25, 1991, Guo
was sentenced to four years in prison with a one-year deprival of
his political rights because of his law-violating offences. After
his parole in 1993, Guo was sent to work at the Jianchang
Machinery Plant in Xiangfan City, Hubei Province, in accordance
with his own wish.
</P>
<P>
However, Guo kept staying in Anyang City, Henan Province, where
he later raped six women, married or unmarried, in defiance of
laws, by tempting them with the ways of talking about love affairs
or buying houses, which constituted hooliganism.
</P>
<P>
Guo has confessed to all his crimes, which have been proven by
the evidence and testimony of many people.
</P>
<P>
On November 21, 1996, the Beiguan District Court in Anyang
City, Henan Province, sentenced Guo to five years in prison, after
hearing the case and in accordance with Clause one of Article 160
and Article 61 of the "Criminal Law of People's Republic of
China."
</P>
<P>
Guo received sentencing entirely because of hooliganism he had
committed and the story of his allegedly helping a dissident
escape to the United States is sheer fabrication, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
Another example included in the report states, "Xiao Biguang, a
scholar from Beijing, was involved in unofficial labor and church
activities." And he was given "the maximum three-year labor
reeducation term in 1996."
</P>
<P>
The actual situation is: Xiao, with only a junior-school
educational background, was formerly a farmer in Dabu Village,
Shazhouba Township, Ruijin County, Jiangxi Province. In 1987, he
went to Beijing University to attended classes and audited courses
in the history of ancient Chinese literature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Criticizes Human Rights Watch for Report (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
But Xiao passed himself off as "an associate professor and a
Ph.D from the Comparative Literature Institute of Beijing
University". He had namecards printed that read "Deputy Director,
Beijing Marginal Science and Technology New Products Manufacturing
Institute; Assistant to the General Manager, Beijing Ante Business
Development Corporation", and he openly swindled the public with
the phony titles and engaged in unlawful activities.
</P>
<P>
On April 12, 1994, Xiao was sentenced to three years education
through forced labor, with the approval of the Beijing Municipal
Administrative Committee of Reform-Through-Labor,
</P>
<P>
The report, which also calls Swindler Xiao a political prisoner,
does not speak the truth.
</P>
<P>
The report terms those criminals who have been convicted of
crimes such as hooliganism, swindling, bribery and embezzlement
and endangering the state security as "dissidents" and "political
prisoners." Furthermore, in the name of human rights, it openly
voices grievances for those criminals who were punished as part of
the "Strike Hard Campaign" for committing murder and robbery, and
for involvement in trafficking of narcotics, arms and even women
and children. This cannot but make the readers suspicious of its
true intentions, the official said.
</P>
<P>
What's worse, the official said, the report's chapter on China
ignores the fact that Tibet is an inseparable part of the Chinese
territory -- a truth that has been recognized by all countries in
the world -- by titling the chapter "China and Tibet" and thereby
purposefully implying a division exists between the two. This is
clearly disrespectful of China's state sovereignty and territorial
integrity, and fully exposes the actual intention of the Human
Rights Watch to split China under the disguise of human
rights. Whether the Human Rights Watch is genuinely caring for
human rights, -- this itself very much merits our "watch".
</P>
<P>
The official noted that it is no accident that Human Rights
Watch neglected to observe rudimental professional ethics, and
wilfully distorted and frame so-called individual cases to make
unreasonable accusations against China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Criticizes Human Rights Watch for Report (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Human Rights Watch was established during the period of the
Cold War to cater to the needs of the West in carrying out its
Cold War activities, and from the very beginning, it harbored a
deep-rooted political bias against socialist China, the official
said, adding that the West, particularly after the end of the Cold
War, has directed the target of attack on the human right issue
towards China.
</P>
<P>
Human Rights Watch has become the most aggressive vanguard of
the anti-China force. In a coordinated move in January 1996,
Western nations raised an anti-China bill at the UN Human Rights
Commission, in which they had meticulously fabricated a report
that lied about a Chinese welfare institute maltreating and
killing orphanage, stirring up a Anti-China sinister wave.
</P>
<P>
In the report, they once again published lengthy accusations
against China. It is not strange to hurl charges at China, he
noted, because the starting point of the Human Rights Watch is not
based on the true conditions with China's human rights but the
political needs of the West.
</P>
<P>
In the eyes of Human Rights Watchers, as long as China remains
a socialist country, it will continue to be a "human
rights-violating state," no matter how much its economy has
developed, how much its society has progressed, how much the
living standards of its people has been raised, or how many
achievements it has scored in the country's democracy, legal
system and cultural and ethical progress been made.
</P>
<P>
In its annual report, the Human Rights Watch claims China has
become a country with a human rights situation that deteriorates
year by year, no matter how it has developed as far its human
rights are concerned. It has once again given the testimony of the
common saying: prejudice goes farther away from truth than
innocence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Criticizes Human Rights Watch for Report (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At present, there are still confrontation and disputes in
international human rights sector, but the momentum of cooperation
and dialogues has also somewhat risen. Some far-sighted people in
the West have also held that the exerting pressure and antagonism
will have no way-out with regard to the issue of human rights in
China.
</P>
<P>
It is regrettable that Human Rights Watch, which is bent on
Cold War thinking, does not want to recognize the healthy
development of the international human rights cause and has spared
no effort in encircling and blocking China on the issue of human
rights.
</P>
<P>
Such words and deeds cannot but be said as a "discordant voice"
that goes against the tide of our times. If Human Rights Watch
persists in acting as the instigator and troublemaker in creating
conflicts over the issue of human rights, it will certainly become
the hinder and stumbling block in the development of the world
human rights cause, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The official expressed his hope that Human Rights Watch will
seriously introspect its conduct and cease to play its inglorious
part in the area of human rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
