<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Soldiers Withdraw From Hebron Army Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Israeli soldiers left their
army headquarters in the West Bank city of Hebron before dawn
today, ending 30 years of Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli news media reported that a convoy of Israeli army
jeeps drove out of the hilltop base toward the central part of
Hebron that Israel is to keep under a self-rule accord signed with
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officers entered the headquarters, symbol of
Israel's rule over the city since the 1967 Middle East War, after
the Israeli soldiers left it.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli withdrawal was included in an agreement on Israeli
troop redeployment in Hebron initialed by Israel and the
Palestinians Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, 400 Palestinian police will be deployed in
80 percent of Hebron, while Israeli troops will patrol the
downtown area, where 500 Jewish settlers live in five enclaves.
</P>
<P>
Between 15,000 and 20,000 Palestinians live in the area that
will remain under Israeli control.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian agreement also contains provisions for
a three-stage Israeli troop withdrawal from West Bank rural areas
by mid-1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
