<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Births Drop for Fifth Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Registered live births in Canada
fell by 1.8 percent to 378,011 in 1995, capping the fifth straight
year of dropping, Statistics Canada said today.
</P>
<P>
The fall reflects both the aging of the baby boomers and the
decline in the fertility rates among women under the age of 30,
the federal fact-gathering agency said.
</P>
<P>
The natural increase of the population, calculated by
subtracting the number of deaths from births, continued to drop in
1995. It decreased by six percent from the previous year to
167,278.
</P>
<P>
The fertility rate, the average number of baby births per woman
in the country fell to 1.64 in 1995 from 1.66 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Canadian mothers were getting older, the agency
said. The average age of women who gave birth in 1995 was 28.8,
compared with 28.6 in 1994 and 26.0 in 1975.
</P>
<P>
Women aged 30 and over accounted for 42.6 percent of all births
in 1995, up from 27.9 percent in 1985 and 19.2 percent in 1975,
the agency added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
