<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Review Losses  of Jute, Textile Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
set up a high-profile committee, headed by Finance Minister A. M.
S. Kibria, to review the situation concerning the loss-incurring
public-sector jute and textile mills and search for a remedy,
official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The committee was formed at a meeting held Thursday with Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina in the chair that discussed various aspects
of the jute and textile industries.
</P>
<P>
Hasina told the meeting that priority should be given to the
employees if they want to purchase the jute and textile mills to
operate on a cooperative or limited company basis.
</P>
<P>
The state-run jute and textile mills, once the cornerstone of
this country's economy, had been disinvested earlier but were
closed down later due to the huge losses they had run up over the
time.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese and Mauritanian Ministers Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NOUAKCHOTT, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen met his Mauritanian counterpart Sidi Ould
Khliva here this afternoon and both parties pledged to boost
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed an agreement on economic and technical
cooperation after the meeting, including a pledge by China to
supply the southwest African country with 1,000 tons of wheat.
</P>
<P>
Qian, also China's vice premier, said that the two countries
have enjoyed good relations since diplomatic relations were set
up in 1965, and that in the current shifting international
situation, it is important that developing countries maintain
unity and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Khliva extolled China's unique role in keeping global peace
and stability.
</P>
<P>
He also congratulated China on its resumption of sovereignty
over Hong Kong on July 1 this year, citing it as the first step
leading to China's final integration.
</P>
<P>
It is Qian's second trip to Mauritania in four years and the
last leg of his five-nation African tour. He earlier visited
Niger, Equatorial Guinea, Sao Tome and Principe, and Cape Verde.
</P>
</TEXT>
