<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cancer, Heart Disease Biggest Enemies for Canadians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Cancer and heart disease are the
two biggest enemies for Canadians, accounting for 54.7 percent of
all deaths in the country in 1995, Statistics Canada reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Stroke ranks third among the leading causes of death,
accounting for another 7.4 percent of deaths in the country in
1995, the federal fact-gathering agency said.
</P>
<P>
For the second year in a row, the number of deaths due to
cancer exceeded those due to heart disease, but the rate of death
per head of the population fell.
</P>
<P>
Death from cancer rose 0.8 percent to 57,810 in 1995, and death
due to heart disease rose 0.9 to 57,000. For cancer, the mortality
rate fell from 188.3 deaths per 100,000 people in 1994 to
184.9 in 1995. For heart disease, the rate dropped from 184.4
deaths per 100,000 in 1994 to 179.9.
</P>
<P>
For strokes, the mortality rate dropped from 49.1 deaths per
100,000 in 1994 to 48.1.
</P>
<P>
AIDS accounted for 0.8 of all deaths in Canada, the agency
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
