<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Parliament Approves New Security Doctrine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Ukrainian parliament today
approved a "National Security Doctrine," whose fundamental
principle is Ukraine's entry into all international security
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Oleg Chernoshenko, vice-chairman the Ukrainian State Committee
on Security and Defense, today praised parliament for passing the
doctrine, calling it an important step in standardizing national
laws.
</P>
<P>
The doctrine clearly sets out the jurisdiction of all
departments involved in national security and methods of
democratic and civil supervision of the military.
</P>
<P>
It gives human rights top priority in the protection of the
national security and promises to eliminate real and potential
threats against Ukraine's security.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine has spent five years drafting the security doctrine.
Work began in 1991 when the state gained independence. Parliament
carried out the first reading of the doctrine in May 1995 and sent
it back for revision in accordance with the Ukraine Constitution.
</P>
</TEXT>
