<HEADLINE> Mauritanian President Meets Chinese Vice Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NOUAKCHOTT, Mauritania, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Mauritanian
President Maaouya Ahmed Taya said here today that his country
will, as always, continue developing friendly cooperative
relations with China.
</P>
<P>
Mauritania has enjoyed a stable political situation in recent
years, and is striving to develop its economy and improve its
people's living standards, Taya told Chinese Vice Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen. Qian arrived here this afternoon for
a 24-hour official visit.
</P>
<P>
Taya said his country stuck to a foreign policy of
independence, peace and neutrality, and had resolutely and
patiently resisted external pressure over past years.
</P>
<P>
Qian, who paid his first visit to the African nation in 1993,
said that China and Mauritania have developed effective friendly
cooperative ties in politics, economy, trade and culture, since
diplomatic relations were set up in 1965.
</P>
<P>
China attached importance to developing ties with Mauritania,
and was willing, together with the African nation, to consolidate
and develop bilateral friendly cooperation, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Both countries belonged to the developing world, and shared
similar or identical views on many major international issues, he
noted. He added that the two had cooperated closely in
international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Qian stressed that all nations, big or small, strong or weak,
were equal members of the international community, and had the
right to participate in international affairs.
</P>
<P>
World nations should support each other so as to achieve common
development, and intervention in other countries' internal affairs
should be opposed, he said.
</P>
<P>
China was willing, on the basis of equality and mutual benefit,
to strengthen and develop cooperation with Mauritania in various
fields, said the Chinese vice premier.
</P>
<P>
Qian visited Niger, Equatorial Guinea, Sao Tome and Principe,
before he arrived in Mauritania. 
</P>
