<HEADLINE> 1997 Modest Economic Growth Expected in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Canada's economy is expected to
grow by 2.9 percent this year as a result of lower interest rates,
a private think tank said today.
</P>
<P>
"The stronger outlook for 1997 reflects the impact of lower
interest rates on residential investment and business plant and
equipment spending," the Conference Board of Canada said in its
latest Canadian Outlook.
</P>
<P>
It also forecasts the Canadian economy will grow 2.7 percent in
1998.
</P>
<P>
However, the board noted that the positive effects of lower
interest rates are being undermined by extremely high household
debt, weak job creation and deep public sector spending cuts.
</P>
<P>
"Canadians remain concerned about high household debt, job
security and income prospects," said Jim Frank, the board's vice
president and chief economist.
</P>
<P>
With domestic demand growth less than 2 percent, an output gap
exceeding 4 percent, and severe government cutbacks, a further 25
basis point easing in Canadian short-term rates is anticipated by
mid-1997, the board added.
</P>
<P>
The board also expects further appreciation of the Canadian
dollar, saying the currency is forecast to reach 76.5 U.S. cents
by the end of 1998. It is now trading at 75 U.S. cents. Some
analysts believe the currency could go as high as 78 cents this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
