<HEADLINE> Argentina Considers U.S. Sanction Unfair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Argentinian President
Carlos Menem has labelled "unjust" the United States' decision to
withdraw 50 percent of Argentina's duty-free privileges in the
America's market.
</P>
<P>
"It is a completely unfair sanction which does not agree with
reality," President Menem said today on state television.
</P>
<P>
Acting U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky announced
her government's decision Wednesday to put higher tariffs on 260
million U.S. dollars worth of trade with Argentina, but to suspend
it until March 1, giving both countries time to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
United States pharmaceutical companies complained that their
products were not being protected by Argentina's current copyright
laws and demanded the Clinton government sanction Argentina.
</P>
<P>
The Argentinian Congress has approved a bill, at the call of
Cilfa (the organization representing Argentinian laboratories),
which permits the country's pharmaceutical industry to copy
foreign companies' patents over a period of time.
</P>
<P>
Despite of his regret, President Menem said the U.S. measure
would not damage bilateral relations and Argentina would seek to
settle the dispute through dialogue. 
</P>
