<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadians Enjoy Longer Lives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Life expectancy rose slightly to
new highs for men and women in Canada in 1995, while the gap
between the sexes narrowed, Statistics Canada said today.
</P>
<P>
Life expectancy was 81.3 years for females and 75.3 for males,
representing a gain of 0.1 years for women and 0.2 years for men
over 1994, the federal fact-gathering agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agency said the gap in life expectancy between Canadian men
and women, which was 6.0 years in 1995, had narrowed considerably
over the past 17 years.
</P>
<P>
In 1971, life expectancy was 7.0 years longer for women than
for men. The gap peaked at 7.5 years in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 25 years, life expectancy had gone from 69.7 to
75.3 for Canadian men, and from 76.8 to 81.3 years for Canadian
women. For both sexes combined, it rose from 73.1 years to 78.3,
an average annual gain of 0.22 years.
</P>
<P>
Internationally, Japan had the highest life expectancy in 1995,
82.8 for females and 76.4 for males.
</P>
<P>
Among Canada's 10 provinces, British Columbia had the highest
life expectancy, 79.0 years for both sexes combined, while
Newfoundland had the lowest at 77.3.
</P>
<P>
Life expectancy in the two territories was well below that of
the province, the agency noted.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the infant mortality rate in Canada was down slightly,
to 6.1 infant deaths per 1,000 live births from 6.3 in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
