<HEADLINE> 139 Died </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, January 16 (Xinhua) -- One-hundred-and-thirty-nine
youngsters, either involved in or the victims of crime, were
killed in Mongolia last year, according to local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The Mongolia's youth crime rate in 1996 was up 18.7 percent
against the the previous year, compared with the 9.1 percent rise
in the overall crime growth.
</P>
<P>
The number of youngsters killed was up 8.5 percent against the
year before.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,355 minors were recorded committing crimes last
year, of which 302 were still at school. The others were out of
work or away from school, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The youth crime included gang crimes, larceny, rape and murders.
</P>
<P>
Youth crime is seen as a serious problem and unstable factor in
Mongolia, and is attributed to poverty and impaired
ethics. 
</P>
