<HEADLINE> American Balloonist Nears Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 16 (Xinhua) -- American balloonist Steve
Fossett was on his way to complete the Atlantic crossing for a
non-stop around-the-world adventure, according to his spokesman on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday morning, Fossett was 460 kms east of the Azores,
approaching the coast of Africa at a speed of 170 kms per hour,
said Ivory Akande.
</P>
<P>
Fossett flew his balloon "Solo Spirit" at an altitude of 8,000
meters, hoping to become the first person to travel around the
world non-stop in a balloon.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the American was seven hours from Gibraltar and he
would arrive in Morocco by Friday, said Akande.
</P>
<P>
After crossing Morocco, Fossett will fly over Algeria and Libya
or change course over Nigeria and Chad should Libya turn down the
request.
</P>
<P>
A Chicago stockbroker, Fossett, 52, had a distance record in a
hot-air balloon. In February 1995, he traveled 8,700 kilometers
from Seoul to Saskatchewan, Canada.
</P>
<P>
Recently, two other teams of balloonists failed in their
attempts to fly around the world starting from Morocco and
Switzerland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
