<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Tightens Controls on New Department Stores </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital has decided
to watch new department store construction closer to avoid
overbuilding.
</P>
<P>
Sources say that the city, which has some 11 million people,
will delay or halt construction of some new department stores in
keeping with its macro-economic readjustment principles.
</P>
<P>
The city has 65 large department stores of over 10,000 square
meters each, 17 of which opened just last year. Another 110 stores
are planned or under construction in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
From 1986 to 1990, the number had grown to only eight. Experts
note that the current department store boom is characterized by
redundant construction, too rapid growth, and poorly-chosen
locations, all of which have led to lower profits or big losses in
some stores, or even the closing down of a commercial complex,
like the one on Xidan Street.
</P>
<P>
To find better locations, coordinate development, and avoid
overlapping stores, the municipal government will impose stricter
controls on new department store applications and offer assistance
to low-profit communities.
</P>
<P>
A popular pastime for local residents has been going shopping
at the big new department stores over the weekend, but that
pleasurable activity is becoming more difficult when it comes to
choosing where to go because of the large number of new stores.
</P>
<P>
But department stores still mean big business and big profits
in China and a lot more people want to open big department stores
in many other Chinese cities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
