The party, which is under heavy pressure from the opposition
and the president to call an early general election, hoped to get
the right to form a new government headed by SP candidate Nikolai
Dobrev, party chairman Georgi Parvanov told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said the SP was prepared to negotiate with other parties
over early parliamentary elections. He said the SP had agreed to
hold elections at the end of this year, but that an interim
government to rule until then must be led by Dobrev.
</P>
<P>
The SP was ready to negotiate with the United Democratic Front,
the main opposition party, and other political forces over a
national crisis plan, he added.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with SP leaders Wednesday, President-elect Petar
Stoianov, who will take office next Wednesday, said that from a
legal point of view, the SP should have the right to form the new
government and called on political forces to compromise on basic
issues.
</P>
<P>
The political crisis in Bulgaria was sparked last month when
Prime Minister Zhan Videnov resigned amid criticism over the
country's economic and financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The SP, which leads the coalition government and is only half
way through its four-year term, nominated Interior Minister
Nikolai Dobrev as new prime minister on January 8.
</P>
<P>
The opposition, however, did not want another SP-led government
and demanded early parliamentary elections and organized protest
rallies to back their demands.
</P>
<P>
Street protests have been a daily event in the country since
the new year and on January 10, demonstrators descended on the
parliament building, clashing with police. Schools, hospitals and
factories have held a range of protests and students have also
taken to the streets.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria is facing a severe economic crisis. In the first two
weeks of this month alone, the inflation rate reached 30.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The state's foreign exchange reserves have fallen to 500
million U.S. dollars, but the country needs to pay back 1.3
billion dollars in loans this year. The International Monetary
Fund is waiting to start negotiations with the country.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that no single party in Bulgaria can handle the
crisis alone, which could only be overcome through joint efforts
by an alliance of various forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
