<HEADLINE> Ukraine Forced to Streamline Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, January 16 (Xinhua) -- One thousand generals and officers
will be sacked from the Ukrainian Defense Ministry and military
commands this year as high debts force the country to make
sweeping budget cuts.
</P>
<P>
Some 500 military units and organizations will also be scrapped.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Alexander Kuzmuk said the ministry will get
only one quarter of the money it needs from the 1997 budget,
forcing him to launch a major reform of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Given its limited funds, the ministry is to focus on developing
medium-sized bombers, fighters and missiles.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine's economic crisis has forced the defense ministry to
tighten its belt and even sell military assets to raise money.
</P>
<P>
Last year, it raked in 32.6 million hryvnas (about 17.6 million
U.S. dollars) from sales. Some 70 percent of the money was used to
modernize weapons and military technology and 30 percent to build
houses. 
</P>
