<HEADLINE> 13 Percent of Population Live in Poverty in Austria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Nearly one million people, some
13 percent of the population, live in poverty in Austria, press
reports said today.
</P>
<P>
More than half the total, or 500,000 people, are workers,
office workers and government functionaries and nearly an eighth,
130,000, are retired people, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The figures show that 14 percent of Austria's manufacturing
workers, 310,000, live in poverty, as do seven percent (190,000)
of office and government workers. Just over half the unemployed,
70,000 people, are also poor, as are 22 percent of farm laborers,
accounting for 70,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The major causes of poverty are the death of a spouse, divorce,
unemployment, heavy debts and low income including pensions,
said Austria's labour union.
</P>
<P>
Government's plans to cut expenditure have also added to the
burden of poverty, the union said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
