<HEADLINE> Australian Wool Price Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Australian wool prices went up
at sales this week, with the eastern market indicator jumping 33
cents to close at 6.17 Australian dollars (4.93 U.S. dollars) per
kilogram clean.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Council of Wool Exporters (ACWE) said that in
the two weeks of selling since the mid-season Christmas break, the
indicator has risen by nearly 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
ACWE said prices soared during the week across all micron
categories, with the largest increases recorded for wool of 21
microns and finer.
</P>
<P>
But it warned that the boosted prices followed the lowest
weekly offering for the season to date of 53,460 bales at Sydney
and Geelong, resulting in an overall pass-in rate of 3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
"While there is good demand for the best quality wool on offer,
exporters report that the overall market sentiment is being driven
by the relatively small quantities rostered for sale in January,"
ACWE added.
</P>
<P>
The Wool International, while commenting upon the wool prices,
said that due to gradually strengthening demand in Western Europe
and steady demand in China, the price is expected to rise further.
</P>
<P>
Next week's sales will be held in Sydney, Melbourne and
Fremantle, with 74,200 bales rostered for sale.  
</P>
</TEXT>
