<HEADLINE> Income of Chinese Farmers Inreasing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The per capita annual net
income of farmers in China was figured at 1,750 yuan in 1996, 290
yuan more than in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Good harvests of principal crops such as grain, oil-bearing
plants, and sugarcane was given as the major reason for the
increase, "Economic Information Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Other things contributing to the increase were the higher price
of grain and the development of rural industry.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the per capita income of farmers in
economically-developed east China was up by 383 yuan last year to
2,374 yuan, while income of farmers in the country's western part
averaged 988 yuan, a rise of 154 yuan.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate in the income of rural residents in western
China was 60 percent lower than for those in eastern China, the
paper reported.
</P>
<P>
The income of each farmer in rural Shanghai, China's largest
industrial center, was 3,595 yuan, 4.5 times as much as that of a
farmer in poverty-stricken Guizhou province in the southwest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
