<HEADLINE> Asking Questions on Health Care Through Postcards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- China's postal and health care
services have given the stamp of approval to a new way of getting
information about healthcare.
</P>
<P>
A new kind of postcard, which combines the postal service and
health care information, has been introduced.
</P>
<P>
The postcards can be bought for ten yuan in post offices around
the country. Users then mail the cards with details of their
names and questions about health care, and will get prompt and
efficient answers.
</P>
<P>
The use of the postcards is considered a social service and has
gained solid support from the China Hospital Management
Association of the Ministry of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
Under the guidance of the association, hundreds of medical
experts have set up seven large medical data banks, including the
national medical experts' data bank, the national special clinics
data bank, the national medical organizations' data bank, the
national pharmaceutical manufacturers' data bank, the national
medical equipment data bank, the national commercial medical
organizations' data bank and the national patients' cases data
bank.
</P>
<P>
Wu Jieping, vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress, and Chen Minzhang, Minister of Public
Health, have written words of praise and encouragement for the new
service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
