<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soccer City Gives Foul Language the Boot (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, January 17 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese soccer city has cried
foul on the use of four-letter words.
</P>
<P>
Soccer venues are usually the place for outbursts of wild
enthusiasm, particularly when clubs are hunting league titles.
</P>
<P>
Dalian's soccer team clinched the 1996 professional
championship, while their football stadium beat off all rivals to
gain the award for the most polite and orderly sporting venue.
</P>
<P>
Today's well mannered Dalian is a far cry from the city of
years ago. Then north China's largest port in Bohai Bay was noted
for its quarreling, as well as the most uncontrollable soccer
venue.
</P>
<P>
At that time, urban dwellers fell out with people from other
places, and often hurled a string of four-letter words in their
verbal attacks.
</P>
<P>
One time, an overseas Chinese bus passenger politely asked
whether the next stop was the People's Square, his intended
destination. But the response from the bus conductor was
"Nao-You-Bing," meaning "dummy". The impolite aside greatly
infuriated the overseas traveler.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the phrase "Nao-You-Bing" had been the most used
expression in some Dalianers' daily vocabularies in the past.
</P>
<P>
Many residents in Dalian, the most economically developed city
in Liaoning Province, were concerned about the state of
impoliteness, which also worried the city government.
</P>
<P>
Now a city-wide clean-up campaign has eradicated bad language,
and brought in a new era of politeness to Dalian.
</P>
<P>
"Spoken dirty words are sure signs of low individual moral
qualities," said Bo Xilai, Dalian's mayor. "This could stain the
city's image and block our opening endeavors as well."
</P>
<P>
Thus, the city government initiated the massive politeness
project last June, urging the people to comply with moral
standards and speak in a polite way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soccer City Gives Foul Language the Boot (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is part of the city's drive for ethical and cultural
progress, as a gesture to respond to the country's endeavor for
building modern civilization.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all urban residents actively responded to the call,
outlawing callous talk, dirty words and even local accents when
talking with outsiders.
</P>
<P>
Local TV stations have broadcast a discussion program on "how
to be a polite Dalianer" among over 50,000 people in the downtown
districts of Zhongshan and Ganjingzi.
</P>
<P>
The staff in the Dalian Weiman Clothes Company, reputed for its
men's suits, also started their own soul-searching bid.
</P>
<P>
Workers in the company's tailoring department, once renowned as
"kings of dirty words", have created a successful method of
counting oral politeness violations of individuals on a specially
designed form on the wall.
</P>
<P>
The department made quick progress, resulting in a politeness
award issued by their boss.
</P>
<P>
The dirty-word fight has become popular across the board
throughout the city, and the result has turned out to be a
success, which is in step with its fast economic growth and the
residents' improved living standard.
</P>
<P>
In addition to outlawing four-letter words, local officials
called on people to study and practice 50 common daily English
expressions, in urgent need of the city's ambition to be more
foreign-oriented.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996, China has started a massive clean-language campaign
in its tertiary sectors and governmental institutions, including
department stores, restaurants and police stations, to help
improve service quality. Dalian is one of the most successful
cities in this effort. 
</P>
</TEXT>
