<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Droppler's Meteorological Radar Station Operational </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, January 17 (Xinhua) -- A highly sophisticated radar
device that can forecast typhoons and fierce storms has been built
in China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The new 1.87 million US dollar installation is the second
Droppler's radar station -- a state major science advancement
project -- built in China. It has gone into operation in
Guangdong's Shantou city.
</P>
<P>
Huang Kejian, director of the Shantou Meterological Bureau,
said the high-tech radar system has been installed in the city to
improve the monitoring and forecasting of typhoons, torrential
rainstorms and thunderstorms that often hit the city.
</P>
<P>
He said only a few countries, such as the United States and
Canada, have so far developed the high-tech radar
system. Droppler's radar is much superior in detecting natural
disasters than the widely used meteorological radar equipment.
</P>
<P>
The building of the new radar station was completed in three
years. The station includes a special highway to the Qingyunyan
Mountain where the radar station is located, a 1,600 square-meter
building and a telecommunications system.
</P>
<P>
Huang said the computerized system can provide 13 kinds of
radar images which can quickly be transmitted to Beijing and the
provincial capital of Guangzhou by connecting the special computer
system to computers in the two cities.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the new radar station will prove to be very
helpful in forecasting natural disasters, boosting disaster-relief
work in the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
