<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dengue Fever Kills Six in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Outbreaks of dengue fever, a
cholera-like disease, have killed six people in Palembang
Municipality of Indonesia's South Sumatra Province, in the last
two weeks, a health official said.
</P>
<P>
Head of the South Sumatra Health Service Slamet Wy said
Thursday that the epidemic disease is extraordinary and that care
must be taken to prevent the disease from spreading, a report
reaching here today said.
</P>
<P>
He said the toll accounts for 13 percent of 44 people affected
by dengue fever in the province.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, a total of 70 people in South Sumatra died of dengue
fever, he added.
</P>
<P>
Dengue fever, an acute tropical disease transmitted by
mosquitoes, leaves its victims with fever, rashes and severe pains
in the joints and back. The disease, known locally as "muntaber,"
also causes vomiting and diarrhea.  
</P>
</TEXT>
