<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Fails to Meet Privatization Earnings Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government earned
5.6 billion pesos (213.7 million U.S. dollars) from its
privatization program in 1996, or a mere one-fourth of the
targeted 21.5 billion pesos (820 million dollars), a local
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The shortfall in privatization receipts will probably prevent
the government from attaining the 17.5 billion pesos (668 million
dollars) budget surplus it had projected for 1996, the paper Today
said.
</P>
<P>
The government has yet to announce its actual budget surplus
for 1996, but has already hinted that this might fall below the
full-year target.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Finance attributed the lower-than-expected
privatization revenues to the government's continued failure to
dispose of some of its big-ticket assets including the Food
Terminal Inc.
</P>
<P>
The privatization of state-owned assets, which began in 1986,
has been a major source of revenue for the cash-starved government
to beef up its budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the government posted for the first time a budget
surplus of nearly 15 billion pesos (573 million dollars) after
selling off assets worth more than 40 billion pesos (1.5 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
But the government has come under fire from economists and
fiscal experts for relying too much on earnings from privatization
to attain a budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
To lessen fiscal reliance on non-recurring revenue sources, the
government began to pin hopes on its comprehensive tax reform
program to increase tax collections. Most parts of the program
have been passed by the Congress and will take effect later this
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Residents Buy More Hi-tech Appliances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Patterns of consumer spending
in Guangzhou are changing as people's residual income rises,
reported today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Though private cars will continue to be a long-term dream for
most, average families already possess the whole range of
household appliances, a consumer survey shows.
</P>
<P>
Hi-fi systems, personal computers, air-conditioners and
large-screen television sets will top the shopping lists of
consumers in Guangzhou this year, the survey, covering 600
families in 25 areas of Guangzhou, suggests.
</P>
<P>
Over Spring Festival in February, clothing, electrical
appliances, health-care products and tourism services will be in
high demand.
</P>
<P>
Japanese-made television sets, which have flooded into China's
major cities since the 1980s, are still the first choice, the
survey found.
</P>
<P>
More than 28 percent of the families interviewed owned
29-inch-screen television sets. And 10.4 percent of the families
were planning to replace old sets with larger ones in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Air-conditioners were little used in Guangzhou until the
1990s. But the city's hot and humid sub-tropical climate has
persuaded nearly 50 percent of Guangzhou families to equip
themselves with air-conditioners, a lower percentage than Shenzhen
but much more higher than Beijing and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Last year, sales of air-conditioners in Guangzhou increased by
11.8 percent. Experts predict a similar rise this year.
</P>
<P>
Telephones, a symbol of social status five years ago, now ring
in 80 percent of Guangzhou homes. Though the average family makes
less than two calls per day, 10 percent of families said they were
going to purchase mobile phones this year.
</P>
<P>
About 18 percent of families owned personal computers. Most
families seldom used their computers this year. Sales increased
by 7.1 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Due to Guangzhou's traffic jams, the rate of ownership of
private cars is lower than in Beijing, Shanghai or Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
But 25 percent of families owned motorcycles, which are much
more common in south China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
