<HEADLINE> Brazilian President Crosses First Reelection Hurdle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President
Fernando Henrique Cardoso won the first round in his bid for
reelection when the Chamber of Deputies approved a bill today
which would allow him to run for a second term.
</P>
<P>
A special Chamber commission voted 19 to 11 in favor of the law
which will now go to the Senate for consideration.
</P>
<P>
The bill, if it becomes law, would change the current
constitution under which the president, governors, and mayors
cannot serve for more than one term of office.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso, who was elected president in January 1995, is seeking
a second term of office at the next presidential election at the
end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The president has enough support to get the bill through the
Senate, but still needs to drum up backing in the Chamber
assembly, sources say.
</P>
<P>
Opinion polls show that 70 percent of the population supports
Cardoso's reelection because of his success in managing the
economy and reducing inflation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
