<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TV Referees not to Interrupt Soccer Matches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 16 (Xinhua) -- TV replays will not be allowed to
be exploited to interrupt the course of soccer games, said a top
official of the sport's world governing body FIFA.
</P>
<P>
Sepp Blatter, FIFA general secretary, said "we must never allow
television to influence the decisions of referees" because soccer
was a sport played and watched by human being.
</P>
<P>
"Referees will always make errors but we have to live with
those because that is what the game is all about," said Blatter.
</P>
<P>
He explained that TV replays will be used for disciplinary
matters but never to change decisions made on the pitch.
</P>
<P>
Blatter made these remarks when he arrive here for next
summer's Four Nation Tournoi de France which features Brazil,
England, Italy and the host.
</P>
<P>
During the tournament, referees and their assistants will be
connected by radio, allowing them to make instant contact if an
incident occurs on the pitch. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Increases its Foreign Debt Payments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Brazil will pay off 17.5
billion U.S. dollars from the principal of its foreign debt this
year, a 50 percent increase over 1996, the Brazilian Central Bank
said today.
</P>
<P>
A bank communique said today that in 1997 the country would
disburse much more of the interest on its foreign debt than in
1996 when 11.3 billion dollars in interest was paid up to last
November, 10 percent more than 1995.
</P>
<P>
The rise in payments was attributed to a bigger inflow of
capital into Brazil and better conditions on the reimbursements,
Geres Ayres, adjunct head of the Central Bank's Foreign Debt
Department, said.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's foreign debt rose from 129.3 billion dollars in 1995
to 159 billion dollars in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
