<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Following are major news items
in leading Australian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- The Murdoch and Packer media empires (Australia's two most
powerful media tycoons) have ended their year-long rift, signing
separate agreements yesterday that deliver the Nine Network a
Super League telecast and ending a court battle over television
programming.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- Australians will be able to slash their international
telephone bills by 75 percent from next week by using the Internet
instead of the telephone network. The new service is the first in
the world to offer Net phone calls using standard touch-tone
phones without extra computer equipment.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- The Victoria government may channel its Olympic funding away
from the Australian Olympic Committee and direct it to athletes
and sporting bodies after controversy surrounding the AOC's
investment strategy.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- The first transgenic crop to be commercially released in
Australia -- Monsanto Inc.'s pest-resistant cotton -- has seen a
major reduction in chemical use half way through its first growing
season, but concerns have been raised over several incidents of
poor performance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
