<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bodies of 88 Killed in Bosnian War to Be Exchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Bosnian Serb Commission
for prisoner release and exchange of dead bodies said on Thursday
that Serbs and Muslims would soon exchange 88 bodies.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the state commission Jovo Rosic told Tanjug in Serb
city Banja Luka in northwestern Bosnia that the exchange would be
made within the next 10 days under an accord reached in Banja Luka
earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
Rosic said Muslim Commission Chairman Amor Masovic had agreed
that the bodies of 50 killed Serbs should be turned over to the
Serb Republic in the next 10 days at the latest, in exchange for
the exhumation of 38 Muslims.
</P>
<P>
According to the International Committee of the Red Cross,
although the Bosnian civil war was ended more than a year ago,
thousands of people from the three ethnic groups are missing, many
of whom are believed to be killed and buried in mass graves.
</P>
<P>
Rosic also said that an agreement had been struck with Bosnian
Croat Commission Chairman Berislav Pusic a week ago to open mass
graves of Serbs in Grahovo and Jajce, central Bosnian towns which
had been in Serb control until the Muslim-Croat offensive in
Autumn of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The exhumations, however, would have to be postponed because of
a thick blanket of snow and poor weather conditions, and would
certainly be carried out as soon as the situation on the ground
allowed, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
