<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ireland Starts Talks with Egypt, Russia on Beef Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Irish government ministers have
started urgent talks with their counterparts from Egypt and Russia
in an attempt to dissuade them from extending their bans on Irish
beef exports, according to press reports from Dublin.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has imposed a six-month ban on Irish live cattle and
Russia has threatened to extend its three-month exports ban since
the Irish government announced earlier this month the number of
new cases of mad cow disease last year had reached a record high
of 73.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian and Russian government delegations have arrived in
Dublin to decide whether Ireland's claims that it had the world's
most stringent controls were enough to change their minds.
</P>
<P>
The loss of Egyptian and Russian exports, the biggest importers
outside the European Union (EU), could cost the Irish beef
industry 240 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
An Irish Ministry of Agriculture spokesman is quoted as saying
earlier today: "When you consider that we have seven million head
of cattle, 73 cases is not many."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Irish farmers blame the government for not
controlling the use of scrapie-infected bone and meat feed, which
is believed to be the cause of mad cow disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
