<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK Agrees Briefing Date </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department on
Thursday said the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) has
agreed a formal U.S.-South Korean briefing on Jan. 29 over a
proposal for four-party talks on the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking forward to these talks because we want to
proceed with the peace treaty for the Korean Peninsula," State
Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
No venue for the briefing has been agreed yet, according to
Burns. But other officials said it was most likely to be New York,
where DPRK has a U.N. mission and where U.S.-DPRK talks have taken
place in the past.
</P>
<P>
The proposal for four-party talks, grouping DPRK, South Korea,
the United States and China, was launched last April by U.S.
President Bill Clinton and South Korean President Kim Young-Sam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
