<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Discusses Foreign Policy with Advisers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today met with his foreign policy advisers to work out his
second-term strategic goal in European security, including the
expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said the hour-long meeting
was the first in a series of foreign policy meetings Clinton will
hold in coming weeks on U.S. global strategy.
</P>
<P>
"The future of a united integrated Europe and Russia's
relationship to that united integrated Europe, which is one of the
key foreign-policy areas that the president will be working on in
his coming term" was discussed in the morning meeting, McCurry
said.
</P>
<P>
Outgoing Secretary of State Warren Christopher, Secretary of
State-designate Madeleine Albright and top National Security
Council officials were attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, who
just returned Wednesday night from his shuttle tour to Paris,
Bonn, London and Brussels, reported his consultations with
European and NATO leaders over NATO's expansion agenda in detail
and the effort to create a Russia-NATO charter.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of 16 NATO countries are to meet in Madrid on July 8-9
to formally invite some of the former Warsaw Pact members to join
the western alliance.
</P>
<P>
The NATO expansion plan was strongly opposed by Russia, which
considers it would threaten its security and create new divisions
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
As a measure to calm the Russians, alliance officials want to
negotiate a special charter with Moscow that would ensure Russia
did not feel excluded from the new European security structures
but was engaged in a close and cooperative relationship with NATO.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana is to begin negotiations
in Moscow on Monday with Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov
on the charter, in which Russians want the West guarantee that
NATO would not deploy nuclear weapons on the soil of the proposed
new members.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the United States and its allies were
discussing ways to let Russia consult on NATO operations in the
same way NATO and Russia worked together toward achieving peace in
Bosnia. But NATO would not give Russia the veto power over NATO
decisions.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and his top aides have identified six strategic global
priorities for his second term, including, besides Europe, U.S.
relationship with Asia, dealing with challenges of terrorism, drug
trafficking and international crime proliferation, dealing with
regional disputes, according to McCurry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
