<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Milosevic: Political Difference Must Not Block Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Serbian President Slobodan
Milosevic said Thursday political and party disputes should be
resolved in a constructive and democratic way, in which the
government and its ministries have a special role.
</P>
<P>
While discussing economic situation and new year economic
policies with Serbian Prime Minister Mirko Marjanovic, Milosevic
said political differences should not be the cause of any blockade
in the economic development and normal life, official news agency
Tanjug said.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic also noted that the safeguarding and strengthening of
the country's political stability "is of immense importance for
Serbia, since confrontations effected by political differences
inflict both political and great economic damage on the country
and impede the attainment of developmental, economic and social
goals.
</P>
<P>
The Serbian opposition coalition Zajedno has been staging
protest demonstrations over the past 58 days in capital Belgrade
over the annulment of the November 17 local election results,
causing a political crisis in the Yugoslav republic. Zajedno
claims victory in 14 big cities in Serbia and demands the full
recognition of their victory in the local elections.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic and Karjanovic had also discussed about preparations
for structural and ownership changes in the republic's economy,
Tanjug said.
</P>
<P>
The Serbian government and other institutions are working on
adjusting economic legislation to the needs of effective economic
activity and a speedy integration of the Yugoslav economy into
world economic processes, it added.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia is eager to join some key international financial
institutions which can provide large sum of loan to revive its
economy wrecked by the four-year international sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The Serbian president and the premier agreed that the economic
policy for 1997 should also be based on reforms, with the reform
of banking system as priority, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
President Milosevic underscored the great importance of the
upcoming changes, and said the reforms would step up economic
recovery and open prospects for stepped-up development, as major
conditions of the country's stability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
