<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Car Bomb Attack Injures Two People in Southern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Two people were injured in a
car bomb explosion in Yugoslavia's southern city Pristina early
Thursday, Tanjug news agency said.
</P>
<P>
University Chancellor Radivoje Papovic and his driver Nikola
Lalic were injured when the explosion occurred about 50 meters
from Papovic's home at 8:45 in the morning.
</P>
<P>
The Audi, carrying Papovic, was thrown off several meters by
the bomb, activated in a parked car.
</P>
<P>
The two injured were taken immediately to a hospital in
Pristina, the capital city of Kosovo province, for treatment.
Tanjug quoted hospital sources as saying that they were hurt in
head and body but not in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
No one has claimed responsibility to the attack and police have
been making investigation on the incident.
</P>
<P>
An examining magistrate in Kosovo said on Thursday that
morning's attack on the Pristina University chancellor had all the
hallmarks of a terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
Pristina magistrate Danica Maksimovic said the explosion had
taken place in a side-street in Pristina, had been activated from
a distance, Tanjug reported from Pristina.
</P>
<P>
Papovic, who was hurt in the eye, was later flown to a Belgrade
eye clinic for further treatment after he and Lalic had been
treated for head and body injuries and burns, Pristina Surgical
Clinic Administrator Andrija Tomanovic said later in the day.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the terrorist attack was condemned by the ruling
Socialist Party of Serbia (SPS) Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The SPS main committee press service said in a statement that
acts of provoking of and inciting to inter-ethnic enmity and
hatred were aimed at jeopardizing peaceful coexistence of all
citizens of Serbia's southern province of Kosovo based on the
principles of national equality.
</P>
<P>
"Serbia's citizens will not allow Serbia and Federal Republic
of Yugoslavia to be destabilized by internal enemies working
against the interests of their own country backed by foreign
factors," it said.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million population are
ethnic Albanians who wish to gain independence from Yugoslavia and
merge with neighboring Albania. There have been many clashes
between local Albanians and Serbian police in the province in the
past, leaving dozens dead and injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
