<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S Says Syrian-Israeli Talks Unlikely to Start Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Thursday that the conclusion of the Hebron accord between the
Israelis and Palestinians did not mean Syrian-Israeli negotiations
would immediately go back on track of the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns, while hailing as
"encouraging" the agreement reached at Tuesday midnight on Israeli
troops' pullout from the West Bank city of Hebron, told reporters
that this progress on the Israeli-Palestinian track of the peace
process "stand on its own," and "there is no indication right now"
that Syria and Israel are about to begin their peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Washington "has had as a long-term goal the reinvigoration of
the Syrian-Israeli peace negotiations," Burns said. But "do we
think that those are imminent? No, we don't."
</P>
<P>
Syrian-Israeli peace negotiations were suspended nearly a year
ago as both sides were snagged over security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations were postponed to even more remote time when
Likud leader Benjamin Netanyahu became new Israeli prime minister
after a election victory in last May.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu deepened rift between Syria and Israel when he
rejected the land-for-peace formula and insisted that negotiations
should be resumed without preconditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Paliameng Approves Hebron Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Knesset (Israel's
parliament) tonight ratified the long-awaited Hebron accord,
giving the greenlight to the Israeli army to redeploy its
troops in the West Bank town.
</P>
<P>
After more than 11 hours of intensive debate, the Knesset
approved the accord by a large majority, an 87 to 17 vote
with one abstention, due to the strong support by the
Labor-led opposition.
</P>
<P>
The accord was initialed Wednesday morning at the end of
a summit meeting between Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority President Yasser
Arafat, held at the Erez checkpoint between Israel and the
Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
In the early hours of this morning, the Israeli cabinet,
after close to 12 hours of deliberation, approved the
agreement by an 11 to 7 vote, followed immediately by the
dramatic resignation of diehard opponent Science Minister Ze'ev
Begin. 
</P>
