<HEADLINE> Lesotho's Ruling Party Splits: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho's ruling
Basotholand Congress Party (BCP) has split, Information and
Broadcasting Minister Monyane Moleleki said today.
</P>
<P>
Moleleki was quoted by South African Press Association as
saying in capital Maseru that a rift has developed between two
factions in the party as a result of a high court ruling that the
BCP Executive Committee elected in 1996 was invalid.
</P>
<P>
A dispute has developed between members of the invalidated
committee and an old executive committee elected to office in
1995.
</P>
<P>
Moleleki, also a senior BCP member, said the old committee
consisted of people "elected unconstitutionally", adding that
they have rebuked BCP leader Ntsu Mokhehle on a number of public
occasions.
</P>
<P>
He said members of the old committee challenged the
constitutionality of the committee elected last year, of which
Moleleki is a member, resulting in its invalidation.
</P>
<P>
The minister asserted that there are fundamental differences
over whether or not the party's constitution had been violated
during the party's annual congress in March last year when the
new committee was elected.
</P>
<P>
After the election, four constituencies of the BCP made
petitions to the High Court, charging that Mokhehle had violated
the BCP's constitution.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Moleleki said in a statement that there are
people plotting to destabilize the Lesotho government by taking
advantage of the protracted legal battle.
</P>
<P>
BCP deputy leader Molapo Qhobela, a member of the old
committee, however, denied there is a split in the party ranks.
He said what Moleleki has said in fact has hinted at him.
</P>
<P>
Moleleki refused to identify the people he suspected of
plotting to distablize the government, saying their names would
be published "only when the time is right." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
