<DOCNO> XIE19970117.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-01-16 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament Approves Hebron Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Knesset (Israel's
parliament) tonight ratified the long-awaited Hebron accord,
giving the greenlight to the Israeli army to redeploy its
troops in the West Bank town.
</P>
<P>
After more than 11 hours of intensive debate, the Knesset
approved the accord by a large majority, an 87 to 17 vote
with one abstention, due to the strong support by the
Labor-led opposition.
</P>
<P>
The accord was initialed Wednesday morning at the end of
a summit meeting between Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President
Yasser Arafat, held at the Erez checkpoint between Israel and
the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
In the early hours of this morning, the Israeli cabinet,
after close to 12 hours of deliberation, approved the
agreement by an 11 to 7 vote, followed immediately by the
dramatic resignation of diehard opponent Science Minister Ze'ev
Begin.
</P>
<P>
At 11:00 a.m. local time (0900GMT) this morning, Israeli
Prime Minister Netanyahu opened the Knesset special session in
a speech stressing that Israel was not pulling out of
Hebron, but redeploying in the city.
</P>
<P>
The special session lasted until 11:00 p.m. local time
(2100GMT) tonight, as most of the 120 members of the house
spoke on the issue, before the vote finally took place.
</P>
<P>
Although the Knesset has ratified other international
agreements, including the Camp David Accords and the Oslo
Accords, this is the first time it was voting on an
agreement which has only been initialed and not signed and
implemented.
</P>
<P>
As the Knesset finally passed the accord, the Israeli army,
already began to remove its belongings out of Hebron during
the day, is due to handover 80 percent of the city to
the PNA within hours if not sooner.
</P>
<P>
According to the accord, the Israeli army, after the Hebron
pullback, will redeploy its troops in rural areas of the
West Bank in three phases, with the first one to be
carried out during the first week of March, and the last
to be taken place in mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
Within two months after the implementation of the Hebron
redeployment, Israel and the Palestinians will begin negotiations
on the final status in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
By August 1998, the Palestinians are due to control most
parts of the West Bank except Jewish settlements and what
Israel considers as military areas.
</P>
<P>
In other commitments, Israel agreed to release Palestinian
prisoners and to resume negotiations immediately on opening a
Palestinian airport in the Gaza Strip, as well as a
safe-passage between the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
For their part, the Palestinians agreed to complete the
process of revising the Palestinian National Charter which calls
for the destruction of Israel, to fight terrorists and to
confiscate illegal firearms.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians also agreed to deal with Israeli requests
to transfer suspects and defendants in accordance with the
Interim Agreement, known as the Oslo II accord.
</P>
<P>
Israeli cabinet secretary Danny Nevah Wednesday said that one
of the most important achievement for Israel was a letter of
guarantee to Netanyahu by outgoing US Secretary of State
Warren Christopher.
</P>
<P>
Among other issues, the letter permits Israel to unilaterally
decide the size of the areas it will turn over to the PNA
and ultimately the areas to be turned over in a final
agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
