<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from Middle East Countries:
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Kuwait Investment Authority (KIA) today
sold 30 million shares of its Gulf Bank assets to private
subscribers and investors in an auction.
</P>
<P>
The auction started with a launching price of 10 fils (0.033
U.S. dollars) per share and the race was heated between two
investment companies which were contending on behalf of a group
of investors.
</P>
<P>
Director General of the Kuwaiti Stock Exchange Market Hisham
Al-Oteibi, who represented the Kuwaiti state assets supervising
authority, said the auction ended with a final price of 570 fils
(1.88 dollars) per share for the offered shares.
</P>
<P>
The sale was within the KIA's privatization plan. The KIA will
also offer 60 million shares of its Gulf Bank assets for public
subscription in the near future, KIA sources said.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 1.8 billion U.S. dollars was raised in Kuwait from a
privatization drive following today's public auction of shares
that raised 56.93 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The KIA, the state-owned agency overseeing the privatization
program, so far has finished 17 different privatization projects
in companies where the government owns more than a 10 percent
stake since the sell-offs began two years ago, according to
official figures.
</P>
<P>
The privatization program set out to sell state stakes in
some 62 companies and is due to be completed in 1998.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey will invite bids for the construction of a
water project on the River Manavgat for the purpose of selling
fresh water, local newspaper Daily News said today.
</P>
<P>
The tender of the program prepared by the State Waterworks
Authority (DSI) was published in the Official Gazette, calling
for the submission of bids by February.
</P>
<P>
One of the conditions of the tender is that bidders must be
involved in manufacturing or trade in a field open to the
international market and have an annual sales turnover of at
least 10 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to DSI sources, the project is expected to be
completed at the end of this year, and then the facilities will
be transferred to the successful bidders for a period of 20
years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkey will receive a certain percentage of income
from each cubic meter of water sold, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to have a capacity of transferring a
total of 500,000 cubic meters of water per day through water
pipelines to the coast, where it will be loaded onto tankers.
</P>
<P>
The tender has reportedly aroused interests of some companies
from Israel, Libya, Italy as well as some Arab countries, where sea
water has to be desalted at great cost.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Motorola Israel, a subsidiary of the electronics
giant in the United States recorded sales of more than one
billion U.S. dollars in Israel in 1996, a 30 percent rise
compared with that of 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to today's Jerusalem Post, the Tel Aviv-based
subsidiary also reported a 27 percent increase in exports from
233 million dollars in 1995 to 295.5 million dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The firm beat its Illinois-based parent company in using
digital coding for its data communications products and became
the first international distributor of Motorola products before
being taken in as the parent's wholly-owned subsidiary in 1975.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Bahrain-based Gulf Air has decided to sell six
Boeing-767 aircraft and close routes in a bid to save itself from
falling into a debt trap, the official Bahraini News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after a recent meeting by the Board of
the airline, which is equally owned by Qatar, Oman, Bahrain, and
the United Arab Emirates (UAE), the executive chairman of the
Gulf Air Sheikh Ahammed bin Suaef al Nahyan said in a statement
to the Bahraini News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The regional carrier will sell six planes during the period
from February to July and close some uneconomic routes to help
reduce its debt burden and realize profits, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The routes which will be closed include its flights to and
from New York, Geneva and Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
The carrier has mapped out measures to prevent travelers from
being affected, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf Air's debts are estimated at some 2 billion
U.S. dollars, mostly in bank loans. The debts resulted from a
flurry of buying new aircraft in the late 1980s and opening
uneconomic routes.
</P>
<P>
The debt-ridden carrier currently has 32 aircraft, said to be
far more than its needs to fly a handful of its profitable routes.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the airline recorded its worst annual loss of 159
million dollars, the biggest since the Gulf crisis in
1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
