<HEADLINE> Cofinancing for IDB Projects Mobilizes $2.4 Bln </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Fourteen bilateral and
multilateral agencies provided a total of 2.4 billion U.S. dollars
in cofinancing in conjunction with 1996 lending program of the
Inter-American Development Bank (IDB), the Bank reported today.
</P>
<P>
As in past years, cofinancing was a major instrument in support
of IDB lending, which totaled some 6.74 billion dollars last year
for the economic and social development in Latin America and the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
Cofinancing from Japan ranked the largest during 1996 and
reached a record of 1.2 billion dollars, almost twice as much as
the average amount for that country for the past five years.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank is the main source of multilateral cofinancing,
providing a total of 1.1 billion dollars during 1996. Other
confinanciers also include European institutions, providing a
total of some 92 million dollars for the IDB projects last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
