<HEADLINE> U.S. to Press Canada for Dairy Tariffs Removal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States plans to
continue pressing Canada for the removal of its import tariffs on
its dairy and poultry products, a report said today.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the U.S.-Canada dispute on dairy and poultry tariffs
will become one of the top priorities of the new Clinton
administration, U.S. Agriculture Secretary Dan Clickman told
Canada's Financial Post newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"This concerns us very much," Clickman was quoted as saying.
The recent NAFTA panel ruling that endorsed Canada's import
tariffs "was a very disturbing decision...We are now looking at
our options."
</P>
<P>
The panel ruled late last year that Canada's new import tariffs
on key dairy and poultry products did not violate NAFTA (North
American Free Trade Agreement).
</P>
<P>
Canada imposed the tariffs as part of the new international
trading rules. They replaced quotas it had used for 20 years to
keep out almost all U.S. and European imports.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dairy industry estimates that it could sale as much as
1 billion U.S. dollars a year to Canada if it were allowed open
access to the Canadian market.
</P>
<P>
Clickman said one option available to the U.S. is to try to
force Canada to eliminate the import tariffs during the next round
of farm trade talks starting in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Yet, Canada has already indicated it is not interested in
launching negotiations about the farm issue, the newspaper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
