<HEADLINE> Silicon Valley in Midst of Economic Boom: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Silicon Valley, known as a
center for much of innovation underlying semiconductor and
personal computer, is in the midst of its most remarkable economic
boom in two decades, thanks to the rise of Internet, according to
an annual report of Joint Venture Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, the Valley, which is located in the region south of
San Francisco in California state, has added 125,000 jobs. In 1996
alone, the area added roughly 50,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
The area is headquarters for the leading companies in the
computer-networking business. The 30 largest such companies more
than double their employment from 1991 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Valley's growth has been accompanied by a shift in new jobs
from computer and semiconductor manufacturing to software
development, thanks to the rise of the Internet and the scramble
to exploit it economically.
</P>
<P>
For example, Cisco Systems, the San Jose maker of computers
that route over the Internet, hired about 50 employees a week
throughout 1996. The company has continued to expand and now has
800-1,000 job openings.
</P>
<P>
Still, it is the growth of software companies like Netscape
Communications and Orale that suggests the region's new structure.
Traditionally a manufacturing center, it is being transformed.
</P>
<P>
The rise in software business has brought sharply higher pay in
the high-cost region. In 1996, the average wages grew 5.1 percent
after accounting for inflation-- more than five times the national
average.
</P>
<P>
The current period of economic boom is all the more remarkable,
because only four years ago, before the emergence of the Internet,
Silicon faced a crisis, losing factory jobs and venture capitals.
Last year, however, almost all doubts about the area's future
seemed to have dissipated because of its strong growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
