<HEADLINE> Zambian Museum Robbed of Valuable Artefacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's Livingstone National
Museum was robbed over night of 23 artefacts worth of 850,000
U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Zambia News Agency quoted Southern Division Police Chief
Ephraim Mateyo as saying today a hole was found dug open in the
roof for the thieves to enter the museum's building.
</P>
<P>
The artefacts stolen dated back as in the 1920s. These include
witchcraft objects, wooden bow, masks, Elan fly whisks and
walking sticks with ivory handles.
</P>
<P>
Today police finger print experts are busy sifting through
vandalized collections in the ethnography gallery to take finger
prints of the thieves.
</P>
<P>
''They have taken our most valuable and rare artefacts dating back
to the 1920s. I don't think we shall even get such collections
again,'' lamented the museum director. 
</P>
</TEXT>
