<HEADLINE> French Troops Again Clash with Central African Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 16 (Xinhua) -- French troops killed one rebel
soldier and arrested another in a new clash with the mutinous
soldiers of the Central African Republic this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted an "authorized source"
as saying that rebel soldiers opened fire on a patrol of French
soldiers near the Kasai military barracks in the Central African
capital Bangui.
</P>
<P>
No loss was inflicted on the French side during the clash,
which took place after French soldiers intervened to stop the
rebels from fleecing civilians, said the source.
</P>
<P>
The new incident took place when four African countries, backed
by France, are seeking a solution to the three-month long mutiny,
the third in eight months, against President Ange-Felix Patasse.
</P>
<P>
French troops killed dozens of rebels in a reprisal action on
January 5 after the "assassination" of two French soldiers by
the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The head of the African mediation team, former Malian head of
state General Amadou Toumani Toure, said that a 300-man African
peace-keeping force will arrive in Bangui in three weeks on a
six-month mission.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers from Gabon, Burkina Faso, Mali and Chad -- the four
mediating countries -- and Senegal will participate in the force.
</P>
<P>
France is maintaining a 2,300-strong force in the Central
African Republic, which is the largest military base of France in
Africa after Djibouti.
</P>
<P>
The first secretary of the French Socialist Party, Lionel
Jospin, today again rapped the policy of the government in Central
Africa as "a combination of interference and impotence."
</P>
</TEXT>
